deck_excerpt: MASTER DUEL, META DECK, DAEDALUS, HORUS,
deck_description: There are days when you just want to see the world burn and there is nothing more satisfying than sending all the cards in both players' hands and fields to the graveyard.

deck_excerpt: Blue's deck a very special deck to me
deck_description: A deck that I used for many years and have done good with as I order more cards I'll add to this deck

This idea might not be new - I've tried something similar myself in the past, and I'm sure other people have explored this concept as well - but now with the limitations of Snake-Eye Ash and WANTED: Seeker of Sinful Spoils, and the increased synergy between Vanquish Soul and Snake-Eye with Infernal Flame Banshee in the game, allowing any Rank 4 to be a Snake-Eye combo, I thought this was an idea worth revisiting, and I've been having some success with it in the WCS 2024 Qualifiers event. You can facilitate this strategy by playing Parallel eXceed, which is really easy to trigger by link summoning either Rock of the Vanquisher or Linkuriboh.

Here's how you can get from Vanquish Soul Razen to Snake-Eye combo:

  • Summon Vanquish Soul Razen (Normal Summon or, even better, with Stake your Soul!)
  • Activate the effect, get Vanquish Soul Dr. Mad Love from the deck
  • Link Summon Rock of the Vanquisher using Vanquish Soul Razen 
  • Activate Rock of the Vanquisher effect to Special Summon Vanquish Soul Dr. Mad Love from the hand
  • Activate Vanquish Soul Dr. Mad Love effect to add Vanquish Soul - Continue? from the deck
  • Activate Vanquish Soul - Continue? to Special Summon back Vanquish Soul Razen 
  • Xyz Summon Infernal Flame Banshee using Vanquish Soul Dr. Mad Love and Vanquish Soul Razen 
  • Activate Infernal Flame Banshee effect, search Snake-Eyes Poplar from the deck
  • From here, you can Special Summon Snake-Eyes Poplar from the hand with its effect, get Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye or Divine Temple of the Snake-Eye (depending on your hand, usually you really want Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye but, for example, if you have Diabellstar the Black Witch you can access it that way and get Divine Temple of the Snake-Eye instead) and do whatever Snake-Eye shenanigans you want!

Obviously, depending on your hand, this combo can be adjusted. If you already have Vanquish Soul Dr. Mad Love, you can get a different Vanquish Soul monster, like Vanquish Soul Jiaolong or Vanquish Soul Heavy Borger for example. Or you can get Vanquish Soul Snow Devil if you already have Vanquish Soul - Continue?. Also, if you already have access to Snake-Eye combo (via Diabellstar the Black Witch or Bonfire for example), you can either do the regular Vanquish Soul stuff, or use this "engine" to make a different Rank 4, like Abyss Dweller, which can be very strong against decks like Snake-Eye, Branded or Tearlament (I believe it is actually broken, the only reason it is not more seen in this fire meta is because not a lot of decks at the moment can make a Rank 4 without compromising their main combos).

Some notes about the strategy and individual cards:

  • Parallel eXceed is really good in this deck, being another way to get an easy Rank 4 just by Link Summoning anything, or just generic link material should you need it (if only it was fire, dark or earth it would be perfect). It was already cool in Snake-Eye, since you could get Snake-Eyes Poplar after your Snake-Eye Ash gets Veilered/Impermed, just by summoning Linkuriboh and making the Infernal Flame Banshee. How convenient that Vanquish Soul also has access to a Link-1 with a downward pointing arrow! This is also the reason for playing Salamangreat Almiraj, since it can turn a "brick" hand with a Parallel eXceed into full combo if you can Normal Summon an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Maxx "C" for example.
  • Kurikara Divincarnate is amazing. This card is a powerhouse, and it's easy to search in this deck, destroying many decks when you go 2nd and allowing easy OTKs.
  • You can use Snake-Eyes Poplar effect to put Vanquish Soul Razen from the GY in the S/T zone, so you can also summon it during the opponent's turn using Divine Temple of the Snake-Eye or Snake-Eyes Flamberge Dragon.
  • We all like to draw cards, but don't sleep on Vanquish Soul Heavy Borger burn effect! 3000 damage (1500 on your turn, + another 1500 during your opponent's draw phase) it's huge, sometimes you can even OTK while playing around Nibiru, the Primal Being because of it.
  • If you can resolve both engines, that's awesome, but many times you will use one engine as "bait" and then drop the other to kill your opponent. I'd say that Vanquish Soul is really good at baiting all your opponent's interactions (which also plays well with Kurikara Divincarnate) and leave the coast clear for your Snake-Eye combos to make an appearance, but you can choose if you prefer to do the opposite of course.
  • The Extra Deck is somewhat flexible, you can play other Rank 4 or Link monsters if you so desire. The space for non-engine is not the biggest, and this deck is already 45 cards (which is fine tbh), but you can adjust that as well (I'd prioritize playing Fire/Dark/Earth handtraps though, that's why I haven't included Nibiru, the Primal Being or Effect Veiler, opting for Bystials instead, which are good in a variety of matchups). The side deck has some additional cards you can consider.

All in all, I think this is a fun twist on the current fire meta. I hope you enjoyed the deck, I really appreciate your suggestions and feedback about the list, so feel free to leave them in the comments! It's also my first time making a video to accompany/showcase a deck list, so I also really appreciate feedback on it as well.
A somewhat light alteration to the Structure Deck, it goes all-in on the many forms of Blue Eyes

Symphony of Shine - Agent & Melodious Fusion

This deck takes a unique approach, combining the "Melodious" archetype with "The Agent" cards and a touch of "Hyperion" power.

Core Strategies:

  • "Mystical Shine Ball" Engine: Three copies of "Mystical Shine Ball" fuel Special Summons for various effects. You can use its self-burn ability or banish "The Agent of Creation - Venus" to swarm the field.
  • Melodious Fusion: The "Melodious" monsters work together with "Ostinato" to create powerful Fusion monsters like "Flowering Etoile the Melodious Magnificat" and "Schuberta the Melodious Maestra." These fusions offer disruption, negation, and searching capabilities.
  • The Agent Engine: "The Agent of Creation - Venus" and "The Agent of Destruction - Venus" work in tandem. Use their effects to Special Summon "Mystical Shine Balls" and other Agents for further swarming and advantage.
  • Hyperion Support: "Master Hyperion" and "Majesty Hyperion" provide additional firepower and control options, while "Honest" offers a universal attack boost.

Tech Choices:

  • Hand Traps: "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring" and "Infinite Impermanence" disrupt your opponent's plays.
  • "Herald of Orange Light" Lock: Three copies of "Herald of Orange Light" restrict your opponent's Special Summons from the hand, synergizing with "The Agent" strategy.
  • Pot of Prosperity: This card filters your deck and searches for key pieces.

Extra Deck:

The Extra Deck offers a variety of options for different situations. "Flowering Etoile" and "Schuberta" are your main Melodious Fusions, while "Accesscode Talker" and "Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess" provide powerful Link Summons. "Protector of The Agents - Moon" protects your Agent monsters, and "Sky Cavalry Centaurea" helps recycle resources.

This deck prioritizes swarming the field with "Mystical Shine Ball" and utilizing them for Special Summons and Fusion plays. "The Agent" cards provide additional support, while "Herald of Orange Light" disrupts your opponent's strategy. Be prepared to adapt your Fusion choices based on the situation and use the diverse Extra Deck options to your advantage.

Extra Deck considerations: TY-PHON, Bagooska, Accesscode

Side Deck considerations: Book of Eclipse, Cosmic Cyclone, thrust, change of heart, talents

deck_description: Words cannot describe how much hard it is to lose against this archtype let alone build a deck based around one without any roadbumps in the way whilst doing this.

A Battle Box consisting of four decks helmed by the Charmers of each element. Fire, Water, Earth, and Wind. Each deck will have cards that date back to the beginning of the game all the way to 2008. The goal is for each to be balanced around eachother and to offer a slower, more old school style of play to be played against eachother.

If you open any scareclaw level 3:

  1. Summon the level 3, Link Summon Scareclaw Light-Heart, and search Primitive Planet Reichphobia.
  2. Activate Primitive Planet Reichphobia and search Scareclaw Reichheart  
  3. Special Summon Scareclaw Reichheart and search Scareclaw Arrival 
  4. Activate Scareclaw Arrival and summon back the level 3 in GY.
  5. Link into Scareclaw Tri-Heart and activate it's effect to summon the level 3 (search Scareclaw Kashtira)
  6. Activate Scareclaw Kashtira and banish Scareclaw Reichheart if you have defanging or banish Scareclaw Light-Heart if you're worried about bystiels. 

Tips

  • Always go into Kashtira plays before summoning any level 3s
  • Don't be afraid to link Scareclaw Kashtira into Scareclaw Light-Heart intstead of Kashtira Shangri-Ira 
  • Scareclaw Defanging can protect from most board breakers and from S:P Little Knight and Dyna Mondo 
  • ALWAYS TRY TO GET THE DRAW OF Scareclaw Reichheart (If you can)
  • Before going into the extra deck, check to see if you have the field and if there are 3 or more defence monsters; You can activate Primitive Planet Reichphobia to pop any card your opponent control. No more risky backrow or problematic monsters.
  • Sky Striker Mecha - Widow Anchor can be used right after you summon Scareclaw Tri-Heart to clear the field. You can also do this during Draw Phase.
  • You can play 3 of each hand trap but, you might not draw enugh engine and you really need the widest range for Crossout Designator.

Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying vs. Chaos Angel

  •  You use Chaos Angel only if you need the ATK, you need a towers, or there is little in your opponent's GY.
  • You ussually use Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying to banish your opponent's stuff because the materials used can be used to summon Vicious Astraloud 
  • These are also somtimes used instead of going into the Scareclaw Tri-Heart because of certain cards on the field. Use Cross-Sheep to boost ATK and smmon a card from GY before going into the synchros and Vicious Astraloud 

Side Deck:

  • Change of Heart, Mind Control, and Sky Striker Mecha - Widow Anchor are to take monsters so you can OTK through boards. Also Scareclaw Tri-Heart uses generic Effect Monsters, so you might be able to go into Scareclaw Tri-Heart early. But beware, Scareclaw Light-Heart needs the EMZ to search Primitive Planet Reichphobia 
  • Harpie's Feather Duster & Lightning Storm: Good board breakers + crossout targets so your Scareclaw Defanging and/or Scareclaw Tri-Heart don't die to quickly
  • Scareclaw Decline: This is for the grindgame. You might side this in if your opponent uses cards that slow the game down.
  • Scareclaw Straddle: This can be targeting protection but more than that, it can be used to get over any big towers such as Expurrely Noir
  • Anti-Spell Fragrance: Side in when going first; This can stop any spells your opponent may activate.
  • Evenly Matched: You may love your BP, but you may side this going second if your scareclaws just can't play through their deck choice. So, you can set up traps like Scareclaw Twinsaw and Scareclaw Sclash.     

I:P Masquerena 

You can use I:P to go into Underworld Goddess of the Closed World, S:P Little Knight, Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, or Scareclaw Tri-Heart. You ussually don't go into another Scareclaw Tri-Heart, however, sometimes your opponent can't out the big guy and especially 2 of them, or 1 of them with effect protection that isn't from Scareclaw Defanging. You can use Underworld Goddess of the Closed World with 2 level 3s to just basically take a monster (tribute it) since Scareclaw Tri-Heart summons two, you have mat for I:P Masquerena on your opponent's turn. This also applies to Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess. Uhh... really don't need to really explain S:P Little Knight, do I?   

Author's Note(s)

Also, if you want, you can use Rescue Cat and run 3 of each scareclaw level 3; This way, you might actually make Scareclaw Alternative playable. Also, if you do this, you may want to run board breakers in main. It really pains me to see this many hand-traps in my deck personally. I also really want to see me running 3 Visas Starfrost, 3 of my favorite scareclaw boys, 3 Scareclaw Arrival, and 3 Primitive Planet Reichphobia. The other scareclaw spells/traps are still very cool... but it's not their time to shine just yet. Also... NO I'M NOT GOING TO USE MANNADIUM! Kashtira Shangri-Ira can also be fun to summon because of emotional damage but, it's also really good for the grind game.

deck_name: Brave Witches of the White Forest
deck_description:
WARNING: This deck does have the tendency to brick a non-zero number of times.

This deck aims to use the synergies between the Adventure engine, Diabellstar the Black Witch and the White Forest and Witchcrafter archetypes. This allows for a very flexible and mid-range playstyle.

 

Diabellstar the Black Witch

Being released in late 2023, it is more in line with the higher power cards released around this time. This card can set up either your combo in fire-centric decks with 'Original Sinful Spoils – Snake-Eye', or set up a robust resource loop with 'Sinful Spoils of Betrayal – Silvera'.
We are using this resource loop to make sure the floor of our deck never stoops too low for very minimal space in our deck.
The synergy of 'Diabellstar the Black Witch' is that you can discard any type of discard fodder from any of the other parts of the deck. So, I will go over the specifics when we reach the other parts of the primer.

 

The Adventure Engine

When Adventure was released in early 2022, it was immediately known as an extremely strong engine. It gave an omni-negate and a bounce on a spell card in exchange for only the effect of your normal summon.
While the omni-negate is very useful, the main use of this engine is the availability of searchable spell cards. 'Fateful Adventure' searches floatable equip spell cards, making them great discard fodder for all the other engines.

The synergies
Diabellstar the Black Witch
'Water Enchantress of the Temple', 'Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon' and 'Starlit Papillon' make great discard fodder for the summon of 'Diabellstar the Black Witch'.
'Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon' and 'Starlit Papillon' are especially useful due to re-equipping once per turn, meaning they can be sent again on the opponent's turn when you've sent 'Diabellstar the Black Witch' for 'Sinful Spoils of Betrayal – Silvera'.

The White Forest archetype
Due to 'Diabellstar the Black Witch' and the White Forest archetype being so closely related, 'Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon' and 'Starlit Papillon' also make good discard fodder for their effects.

The Witchcrafter archetype
Similar to the other parts of the deck, the spells are very useful for discard fodder. One small thing that Witchcrafter monsters benefit from more than White Forest monsters or 'Diabellstar the Black Witch' is that 'Fateful Adventure' can search when your opponent summons a monster as well when playing 2 equip spells. This makes sure that you always have one spell card available to discard on your opponent's turn.

 

The White Forest archetype

This archetype was teased last April. When I tried the deck pure it felt relatively weak. With this I realised it could synergize really well with Witchcrafters, due to their similarities. We aim to use the free bodies gained to create their boss monsters while losing minimal resources, bolstering our end boards and granting more avenues to break our opponents' end board. 

The synergies
Diabellstar the Black Witch
Due to the relatively low amount of White Forest cards in our deck, we don't gain as much use as we would when playing the pure variant of the deck. However, we are playing 'Asteria of the White Forest' and 'Risette of the White Forest'.
'Asteria of the White Forest' can summon itself very easily from the graveyard, making it good discard fodder on your own turn. 'Risette of the White Forest' adds itself back to your hand very easily on your opponents' turn, granting you potential discard fodder when you've sent 'Diabellstar the Black Witch' for 'Sinful Spoils of Betrayal – Silvera'.

The Adventure engine
Because most of the White Forest monsters send spell/traps from hand or field to the graveyard, 'Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon' and 'Starlit Papillon' make great resources for their effects.

The Witchcrafter archetype
All the spells from the Witchcrafter archetype add themselves back from the graveyard eventually, making them great discard fodder for their effects. 'Witchcrafter Patronus' also allows to shuffle back a spent 'Rcia of the White Forest', making sure you can take advantage of the summon and search effect of 'Risette of the White Forest' multiple times.

 

The Witchcrafter archetype

While the Witchcrafters are the oldest and weakest archetype here, that does not mean it is at all useless, especially with the new support in Magnificent Mavens. The aim here is to use the Witchcrafter cards as the bulk of the strategy, due to their high power locked in the high level Witchcrafter monsters like 'Witchcrafter Madame Verre' and 'Witchcrafter Vice-Madame'.

The synergies
Diabellstar the Black Witch
Because the spell cards are all recyclable, they make great discard fodder, much like the other spell cards in the deck.

The Adventure engine
While at first it seems like anti-synergy, because you can't summon the high-level monsters due to the lock on 'Rite of Aramesir', this is not the case at all. This is because all the small monsters' effect to summon a monster from deck is a quick effect, meaning you can access them on your opponent's turn instead. This also triggers 'Fateful Adventure' again, re-filling your hand with a spell for the high-level monster that was summoned.

The White Forest archetype
Because 'Legend of the White Forest' sets itself from monster effects, it is the perfect discard fodder for the Witchcrafter Monsters. It allows to summon the high-level Witchcrafter monsters without losing the card advantage.

 

Some notable cards and their uses

Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous
This card is quite specific to your starting hand, but the main use is quite clear; to summon 'Witchcrafter Vice-Madame'. This card was chosen because it is summonable from deck with the effect of 'Asteria of the White Forest', it is the fusion spell and half the fusion materials for 'Witchcrafter Vice-Madame'. This makes it the somewhat cumbersome fusion summon very low-investment.

Witchcrafter Patronus
This card is the meat and potatoes of the strategy. This is because it can shuffle ANY spellcaster into the deck. This actually has many applications for every part of the deck.
First of all, if no part of the Witchcrafter archetype was found with your starting turn, it allows you to easily use any part of your setup to get to them. Shuffle anything back for 'Witchcrafter Creation' and you're off to the races.
Secondly, besides shuffling from the graveyard, it can shuffle from banishment. This means you can shuffle back an inaccessible 'Diabellstar the Black Witch', making it available again. Or it can reset the small Witchcrafters, 'Water Enchantress of the Temple' and 'Rcia of the White Forest' after using their graveyard effects.
Thirdly, you can dodge certain disruptions your opponent might be running. Cards like the Bystials and 'Called by the Grave' won't resolve because their target can no longer be banished, because of the spell speed 2 shuffle. This insulates your strategy very well and allowing you to edge out your opponent in the grind game.
And these benefits are all on top of going +1 every turn!

Reasoning
While this card is individually very strong, it has a secondary purpose in our deck. Because it mills until it finds a monster, it allows us to mill Witchcrafter spells. However, due to the random nature of this card, it is very cuttable for a more consistent strategy.

Droll & Lock Bird/Effect Veiler
Both are incredibly powerful handtraps, especially in Snake-Eye format. What's more is that they are spellcasters, allowing you to shuffle them back with 'Witchcrafter Patronus', gaining all the benefits from said card.

deck_excerpt: Royalty reigns in Masterduel ladder in the form of the regal Fire Kings!
deck_description:
A bunch of new Fire King support cards has arrived in Masterduel - enabling the strategy to effectively be played pure. Fire King's consistency, power and gameplan has been buffed and streamlined so that now it has a even more powerful gameplan, a robust grindgame and the ability to field 15+ staples in the maindeck! 

Since the "pure" version of this deck is relatively simple, I'm not going to write a gigantic strategy article on it. If you want a great guide on "pure" Fire Kings, I highly recommend Yacine656's video found here. 

 
Fire King's end board usually consists of a set up Fire King Sanctuary, Fire King Island with at least two level 8s on board (to nuke your opponent's board with Garunix Eternity using Sanctuary's trigger effect) as well as a set-up graveyard full of follow-up. Your hand will also contain several handtraps to augment your board. 
 
While the pure Fire King may seem deceptively simply and therefore, weak - it is surprisingly potent in Masterduel's meta. Nearly every card triggers float effects either from hand, deck or GY. Special summons can be played minimally in this deck to combat Maxx "C," or the deck can combo off with Promethean Princess -> Fire Link 4 fairly competently for a more powerful board. Fire Kings can also generate a ton of advantage and ATK power extremely quickly. The deck also has natural ways to combat the ever common backrow floodgates through Fire King Sky Burn. Fire King monsters on the field can also reliably dodge targeting effects because quick effect in-archetype cards like Sky Burn, Circle of Fire Kings and High Avatar Kirin all destroy your monsters. 
 
When piloted correctly, Fire Kings basically has no "bad match-ups" in today's metagame, since it basically has answers to (almost) everything. Played "pure," Fire Kings might not have as much power as Snake-Eye, Kashtira or Branded, but it makes up for it with its versatility, adaptability and grindgame.  All in all, Fire Kings played as a "pure" deck remains a solid meta choice for Masterduel ladder! 
 
GLHF Duelists!

The Abyss Actor deck is a control-style Pendulum deck that is split into two subarchetypes: The Abyss Actors, who are the Pendulum and Link monsters, and the Abyss Scripts, which are the Spells. It has a unique playstyle that gets Abyss Playhouse - Fantastic Theater onto the field in order to force your opponent to destroy your set Abyss Scripts to trigger their busted effects. Abyss Script - Dramatic Story bounces two cards on the field to the hand, Abyss Script - Rise of the Abyss King adds any combination of two Abyss Actors and Abyss Scripts from your Deck to your hand, Abyss Script - Abysstainment swarms the field with Abyss Actors, and Abyss Script - Opening Ceremony straight-up draws you up to 5 cards. 

With the release of Legacy of Destruction, these theater kids have a new prop for their show: Pendulum Witch . This card + any Abyss Actor is a 1.5 card combo that bridges into Abyss Actor - Curtain Raiser and starts your normal combos. Yeah, it's generic for any Pendulum deck, but is best utilized in this particular deck because of Curtain Raiser's recursion of an Abyss Actor by dumping an Abyss Script and Abyss Actor - Wild Hope being able to search any Abyss Actor upon being destroyed. 

While I don't have time to explain all the different combos, they can vary from a pop of an Abyss Script on quick effect speed thanks to Abyss Actor - Super Producer and Fantastic Theater changing any monster effect to pop a set Abyss Script to an OTK with Abyss Actor - Extras when going second to 4 negates and a Fantastic Theater pop via Wild Hope/Curtain Raiser and Abyss Actors' Dress Rehearsal . Have fun playing this fun and interesting deck!

deck_excerpt: Enjoy the intense power of Branded in this new 60-card version Masquarade turbo!
deck_description:
Okay, so the 60 card limit allowed me to add a lot more than I could in the previous version. The deck is heavily inspired by Galzo's video ln 60 card Branded, but with some changes here and there to fit my playstyle and ideas better.

I put in more Tearlament because thy are all DARK which makes them able to be used as fusion materials for Branded and Despia fusions, as well as mill a lot of the deck and recycle the fusion materials back to the deck. Just like Galzo, the deck is basically Masquarade turbo, so you want to fusion summon both of them as fast as you can. On top of that, many cards like Despian Tragedy and Albion, theShrouded Dragon have GY effects, so it just helps the deck even more. 

More Cartesia, Shrouded and especially Tragedy makes the deck much more consistent. If you mill Tragedy with Tearlaments, you can just add even more Despias to hand for the summon of things like Masquarade or Quartesis. You do not need all 3 of Branded in Red, most of them are there to be sided and only one to actually be used. 

This time, we do not play Gimmick Puppet Nightmare, so what's the point of Sanctifire then? Well, you can summon one monster to opponent's field and Albaz to yours, then if you have a card in hand (which you most likely will), you can activate Albaz's summon effect to fusion summon during opponent's turn. Also god forbid your opponent milling your deck, because if they mill a Terlaments monster, they practically allowed you to play during their turn.

Overall, this deck still hasn't been tested, but I can already see many things happening if everything goes by plan. Overall, if this deck shows off good, I may even change my other Branded deck as default as use this one! Who knows, by then just gotta test it out!
This deck take advantage of cards like GMDE, Small World, Inferno Tempest, Eater of millions, Banquet of millions and D.D. Dynamite

deck_excerpt: Generaider , Superheavy Samurai , World chalice , World legacy
deck_description:
Hello guys , 

I wanted to update the last build but the new build plays differently. it focuses on ripping the opponent's hand (4 cards usually) and setting negates in the meantime so the game is over on the spot. So there's 2 ways to do that a 1 card combo with only metalcruncher or 2 with Wakauchi or Bike and any Generaider Card.

So the combo starts of with normal summoning metalcruncher searching for bike , bike for wakauchi , scale wakauchi and scale big benkei and search helmet , helmet equip and special summon it. Synchro summon Ib in the EMZ (Important) : Ib chain link 1 to search for monstrosity and wakauchi chain link 2 to set himself in the scales.

So the combo differs in the excution here a bit just to play around nibiru:

     (1) : So if you started with Metalcruncher : You use monstrosity targeting it to summon Harr and Mardel , Mardel search for Boss stage , (if they nib u just negate with Harr) , now link Ib for gravity controller triggering Ib summoning Lee and searching World chalice, Overlay Mardel and Metal cruncher for Jormangander and Activate boss stage. After Resolution activate Jormangander detaching Mardel both draw and attach ( In case you drew into a Genaraider card attach Gravity controller excute like combo (2) and at the end of the combo use Ib and world chalice for I:P and more follow up next turn). Boss Stage Triggers summoning Vala , Harr triggers to Rip one card of the opponent hand. Vala summons Mardel from grave overlay for Phantom Fortress detaching Vala  and rip one then pend summon world chalice and use it  with Lee and controller for Trishula and overlay for Phantom Fortress again and rip another card. now use the both  Phantom Fortresses for F0 and then into Utopic Draco future in the EMZ. Pass turn and during draw phase summon Hela and 3 tokens , Tribute one to bring back Harr from grave. In standby activate Jormangander, again both draw and attach , Harr triggers to rip another card (if u have droll you can chain it and stop them from searching before even searching also the draw of Jormangander turns off Pot of prosperity and extravagance). Ripping 4 cards in total and having 2 negates (omni and monster) which should be more than enough to deal with the last 2 cards even if it isn't you can eat them alive next turn.

     (2) :  Ib for gravity controller triggering Ib summoning Lee and searching World chalice, pend summon world chalice and use it  with Lee and controller for Trishula, use monstrosity targeting it to summon Harr and Mardel , Mardel search for Boss stage , Overlay Mardel and Trishula for Jormangander and Activate boss stage. After Resolution activate Jormangander detaching Mardel both draw and attach, Boss Stage Triggers summoning Vala , Harr triggers to Rip one card of the opponent hand. Vala summons Mardel from grave overlay for Phantom Fortress detaching Vala  and rip one, Vala in grave activate discarding a Generaider card  bringing herself backn, overlay her and Harr for Phantom Fortress and ripping another card.  now use the both  Phantom Fortresses for F0 and then into Utopic Draco future in the EMZ. Pass turn and during draw phase summon Hela and 3 tokens , Tribute one to bring back Harr from grave. In standby activate Jormangander, again both draw and attach , Harr triggers to rip another card.

I tried to optimize the deck as much as possible having as many starters as possible ( 9 one card , 9 semi-one card starter) and I think it's pretty consistant IMO.

For the going second we can afford to play 12 non-engine including shifter because even tho we play pends and Vala it's not that big of a deal especially with metalcruncher combo. but you don't have to play it if you don't want to. However I would consider Droll the staple handtrap here mainly because of his interraction with Jormangander. Laevatein is realy good going second since it can get rid of annoying cards dodging imperms, veilers and skill drain and if that wasn't enough it can pave the way for a big fat Zeus to further break the board. Although I wish we have a 3rd Generaider XYZ ( possibly Fenrir in the future) then there will be no reason to run a 2nd Jormangander.

 For the side deck nothing crazy : Fenrir , talents and nibiru are match dependant and cover alot of ground. Same goes for promethean and Amblowhale. Veidos is experimental to me it's honestly very good into alot of match-ups but it's a turn skipper for kashtira players. The trap allows me to get it back and use it as xyz material or a target for Monstorsity. it's a very intersting card in this deck.

deck_excerpt: Time Thieves jumps back to Ancient Egypt and brings back some Horus monster with them
deck_description:
Using the strenghts of the Horus and Armor XYZ engine, turn the Time Thief deck to a deck that can use the Rank 8 toolbox with ease, and unlock a few neat synergies. As well as finaly make Time Thief Temporwhal a core part of the strategy.

King's Sarcophagus combined with a lot of card that become useful once in the GY, and some retriavable cards (Full-Armored Xyz can be dumped twice, if you don't plan to use it's on field effect, by using Dark Knight Lancer's effect).

King of the Feral Imps, the main access to the Xyz Armor Fortress can search both Suprem Soverein Serpent of Golgonda and Therion "Empress" Alasia (wich can later be summoned targeting it). 

The equip effect of the Therion monsters can trigger Dark Knight Lancer.

And more...

- - - - - -

The ideal non interrupted bord would most of the time end on Dark Lancer, Therion "King" Regulus, Gigantic "Champion" Sargas, 3 to 4 material Apollousa, a possible Redeor and/or both set Time Thief Power Reserve and Full Armored Xyz to go into another Time Thief Xyz during the Standby phase.

Putting up a negate under 5 summon is quite easy, and most hands can go through a few interruptions. .

- - - - - 

Things that could be changed righ now : Magicians' soul is really in to fix bad hands and put an Imsety in rotation if not available for some reasons.In a heavy handtrap format, i would swith it for Triple Tactics Talent or Thrust. Once on the field i can only by used as link material. For that reason I could see switching World Gear or Time Thief Double Barrel for a Relinquished Anima. 

I could also see switching The Zombie Vampire in the main for Number 1: Infection Buzz King for time rule reasons as well as getting a look at the opponent Extra-Deck. Although The Zombie Vampire, even if it's a bit risky, can fix youself both by giving you a look at your opponent deck and sending to your GY some of the missing Horus or Time Thief monsters you could need in rotation.

Game 2 going 2nd I would side out the field spells, Terraforming, Suprem Soverien and one of the Time thief trap. Side deck cards depicted here are personnal choices based on my local opponents usual decks, and could be switched for anything. 

And since we go into a lot of rank 4 i could understand siding in a Gagaga Cowboy, jockingly of course.

deck_name: Beginner's Guide to Ice Barrier Runick (Post-BLTR)
deck_excerpt: Thanks to BLTR, the Legendary Frozen Dragons have finally are a competent rogue deck!
deck_description:
Yet another archetype has become besties with Runick, and that is Ice Barrier with its Battles of Legend Terminal Revenge support! 
 
The immense synergy between Guardians of Ice Dragons and the Heroic Runick Spells are due to the fact that Ice Barrier can draw FOUR cards as part of it's main combo while summoning floodgates from deck! All the while, Runick assist the archetype as it weaves through its combo providing extenders and synchro bodies! 
 
The card advantage that both strategies net the duelist result in 7+ cards drawn, with a field full of Ice Barrier floodgates like General Raiho (must discard to resolve monster effect), Medium (Only 1 spell/trap activation per turn) and Georgius (No monster activations in the GY)! The centerpiece that summons these floodgates on your opponent's turn is the new incredibly cool boss monster from Battles of Legend: Terminal Revenge - Lancea, Ancestral Dragon of the Ice Mountain! 
 
Are Ice Barriers finally competitively viable with their new support? I truly believe they are, since in my 50+ test games they fought toe to toe with Snake-Eyes, Branded and Labyrnth! Why not try this cool (pun intended) strategy for yourself! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Like with every Runick combo deck, Ice Barrier Runick is a beautiful synergistic marriage of the two archetypes. 

The ICE BARRIER part of the strategy is composed of 18 cards. There are 9 one card starters for the main combo, that being x3 Revealer, x3 Hexa, and x3 Medallion. x1 General Raiho and x1 Medium are the potent floodgate garnets summoned off of Lancea from deck. x2 Georgius, x1 Speaker and x3 Mirror Master are combo pieces as well as extenders for the deck. Finally, x1 Freezing Chains is also another extender and another search target for Mirror Master if you happen to already have all the combo pieces in hand. In the Extra Deck, one of each Ice Dragon is included since they all float into each other - x1 Lancea, x1 Trishula Zero, and x1 Trishula. 
 
RUNICK offers an alternative win condition of this deck by banishing your opponent's deck. Runick also increases the strategy's consistency and grindgame since it allows for a draw 1-3 per turn. Finally with Runick, it gives Ice Barriers additional bodies body to make synchro plays with. Runick spells also break opponent's boards fairly well when played correctly in tandem with the other archetypes, allowing them to function as pseudo-boardbreakers by baiting interruption to allow Ice Barriers to go full-combo. Runick finally offers solid defensive options, with Hugin protecting against destruction effects, Munin protecting from targeting effects and Geri dissuading the opponent from attacking. The Runick portion of the deck is standard, composed of 19 cards - x3 Destruction, x3 Flashing Fire, x3 Freezing Curses, x3 Slumber, x3 Tip, x1 Smiting Storm, x1 Dispelling, and finally the heart and soul of the deck, x2 Fountain. 
 
The rest of the deck is composed of STAPLES. The staple count is minimal due to the nature of Runick combo decks, and it is only composed of three cards - x1 Called By and x2 Triple Tactics Talent. The staple count can go up dramatically post-siding to 10-12 if you need boardbreakers or handtraps that hardcounter your opponent's gameplan. My personal SIDING PATTERN from most important to least important to take out are - x1 General Raiho, x1 Medium, x1 Speaker, x1 Georgius, x1 Dispelling, x1 Smiting Storm, x3 Slumber. 
 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of Ice Barrier Runick is to control/banish your opponent's resources until they surrender or deck-out. The Ice Barrier portion of the strategy summons floodgates from deck with Lancea. It also has an incredible "draw 4" with the combined synchro summons of Coral Dragon + Crocodragon. Combined with Runick, you should be able to draw 7+, freeze your opponent in their tracks with floodgates - eventually drowning your them in sheer card advantage. 
 
Here are some combo lines for Ice Barrier Runick. First, this is the most basic combo with the safest line of play:
 
Runick Quick Play Spell + Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier + 1 Discard = Runick Fountain (draw 1-3) + Herald of the Arc Light (floodgate and omni-negate) + Dragite (spell and trap negate) + draw 1+. 
  1. Normal summon Hexa Spirit.
  2. Activate Hexa's effect to send to the GY Mirror Master of the Ice Barrier, turning Hexa to level 2. (If your opponent Imperms/Ash/Veiler's this, activate your Runick quick play to summon Generaider Sleipnir to synchro summon Lancea, ending your combo). 
  3. Activate in CL2 to Hexa's effect your Runick quick play spell to summon Hugin. 
  4. Activate CL1 Mirror Master in GY to search for Georgius and activate in CL2 Hugin discarding a card to search for Runick Fountain. 
  5. Activate Georgius' effect to summon himself from hand. 
  6. Activate Georgius' on-summon effect to summon Mirror Master from GY. 
  7. Synchro summon into Herald of the Arc Light using Hugin + Hexa. (This is your 5th summon, if your opponent activates Nibiru you can negate destroy it).
  8. Activate Mirror Master's effect tributing Georgius to summon 3 Ice Barrier tokens to the field and turning Mirror Master to level 5.
  9. Synchro summon Coral Dragon using Mirror Master + Ice Barrier Token.
  10. Synchro summon Dragite using Coral Dragon + 2 Ice Barrier Tokens. Draw 1 card with Coral Dragon's effect. 
  11. If possible, do your Runick stuff to continue drawing cards. If you have more than 6 cards in hand, set some of your Runick quick-play spells. 
Here is the second combo that is slightly greedier but with a stronger endboard: 
 
Runick Quick Play Spell + Mirror Master + Speaker + 1 Discard = Runick Fountain (draw 1-3) + Lancea (summons Ice Barrier anti-effect monster/anti-spell/trap floodgates) + Crocodragon quick effect destroy + draw 4+. 
 
  1. During the Draw Phase, activate your Runick quick play spell to summon Hugin.
  2. Activate Hugin's on-summon effect to discard Mirror Master, searching for Runick Fountain. 
  3. Activate Mirror Master's GY effect to search for Revealer. 
  4. Normal summon Revealer. Discard 1 card to summon from deck Georgius. 
  5. Activate Georgius' on-summon effect to summon from GY Mirror Master. 
  6. Synchro Summon Lancea using Georgius + Revealer. (This is your 5th summon, if your opponent activates Nibiru, you can punish them with Lanceas effect to synchro summon Trishula to banish Nibiru and a card from their hand so they'll only have 3 cards left, while you still have extenders). 
  7. Special summon Revealer from hand. 
  8. Activate Mirror Master's effect tributing Revealer to summon 3 Ice Barrier tokens to the field and turning Mirror Master to level 5.
  9. Synchro summon Coral Dragon using Mirror Master + Ice Barrier Token.
  10. Activate Revealer's effect in the GY to summon 1 Ice Barrier Token. 
  11. Synchro summon Crocodragon using Coral Dragon + 3 Ice Barrier Tokens. 
  12. CL1 draw 3 with Crocodragon, CL2 draw 1 with Coral Dragon. 
  13. If possible, do your Runick stuff to continue drawing cards. If you have more than 6 cards in hand, set some of your Runick quick-play spells. 
 
There are other combos for Ice Barrier Runick, and there are different gamestates that occur especially with all the interruptions and handtraps that occur in the meta nowadays, but generally, endboards are the a mix of Lancea, Crocosaur, Hugin and Fountain. If you have extenders, you might even end up with Toad's omni-negate or Chengying's banish. If you want more Ice Barrier combos, check out the other combo guides on Youtube - but from my experience, the two above combos are the best and most resillient. 
 
Admittedly, going second against a full board with Ice Barrier Runick is difficult, especially since Ice Barriers don't have natural board-breaking ability, you cannot enter battle phase when you use Runick quick-play spells and they don't trade good enough vs. your opponent's resources. That's why the Side Deck is full of boardbreakers for going second! Post-side you should have 12 Runick boardbreakers along with the 10+ boardbreaking staples that you've sided in! After you smash your opponent's gamestate, you should be able to fully combo off with Runick Ice Barrier to defeat your opponent in a grindgame. As you combo, you can break your opponent's board with Coral Dragon's destroy effect, and instead of summoning Lancea, you can summon Chenying to further remove your opponent's resources from the field and GY. 
 
With the unique control and resource advantage both Ice Barrier and Runick offers, your opponent's gameplan should be frozen in it's tracks while you snowball resources to victory!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Similarly to Sky Striker, this is a toolbox control resource deck. It has a high skill ceiling since it factors in a player's decision making, resource management and match-up knowledge. Practice makes perfect with the deck!
  • Ice Barrier Runick can generate so many bodies on board that it can easily OTK your opponent, especially with Lancea summoning free Ice Barrier monsters and all the follow-up the strategy gives you. If you feel your opponent cannot withstand your attack and they're out of resources, try to intentionally hold back from using Runick cards so you can enter the battle phase to finish them off!
  • While the standard deck has 3 staples, post-siding the deck can fit about 12 staples so you can play going 1st and 2nd! The siding pattern from best to take out to worst to take out are x1 General Raiho, x1 Medium, x1 Speaker, x1 Georgius, x1 Dispelling, x1 Smiting Storm, x3 Slumber. 
  • Going second, your win condition is to reduce your opponent's gamestate so that you can fully combo off and defeat them in a grindgame. After simplifying their board with boardbreakers (especially the ones you sided in), use one of the combos states above, except pop 1 monster with Coral Dragon, and instead of Lancea summon Chengying!
  • You can play around handtraps like Droll and Effect Veiler by searching with Hugin and Mirror Master during the Draw Phase. Nibiru can be played around or intentionally played into by summoning Herald of the Arc Light, Toad or Lancea.
  • Remember, Revealer's effect locks you into water monsters, and Mirror Master's effect locks you into water synchro monsters! Be mindful of this as you combo and build your board with specific monsters. 
  • Be mindful of how many monster zones are available to you, since monster zones quickly fill up and clog in this deck, especially with Mirror Master's triple summon of Ice Barrier Tokens. 
  • When synchro summoning, be mindful of the levels your monsters have and as they change to activate their effects! Remember, Mirror Master and Hexa both change their levels as they activate their effects!  
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
The Legendary Frozen Dragons have finally been unsealed in the TCG for competitive play, and when paired with Runick the Ice Barriers sure are competitively viable! I was pleasantly surprised at how resilient and powerful the strategy has become, especially with how it powers through handtraps while simultaneously setting up its gameplan. I find the most satisfying thing about this deck is the INSANE DRAW 4 that Crocodragon + Coral Dragon gives you! Along with the draw 3 that Runick has, you'll find yourself with an overwhelming amount of card advantage to throw at your opponent, while you summon Ice Barrier floodgates!
 
With all the support Ice Barrier has received over the past couple years, especially via the recent Battles of Legend Terminal Revenge, the strategy truly has graduated beyond it's "terrible Duel Terminal" status. I've played a lot of Runick combo variants, but I gotta say this is one of my most favourite!
 
GLHF Duelists!

Para obtener el máximo rendimiento del deck, aquí tienes algunas estrategias y consejos basados en el texto proporcionado:

 

Estructura del Mazo y Construcción:

   - Balance de Cartas: Asegúrate de tener un equilibrio adecuado entre monstruos, hechizos y trampas. Esto permite tener siempre opciones versátiles en cualquier situación del juego.

   - Incorporación de Monstruos Horus: Añadir los monstruos Horus proporciona una gran sinergia con las cartas de Dark World, permitiendo combos más efectivos y estrategias de control.

 

Combinaciones y Estrategias:

   - Usar Genta y Rainbow: Genta te ayuda a buscar "Gates of Dark World" y Rainbow te permite agregar monstruos de nivel 5 o más. Esta combinación te proporciona una base sólida para invocar monstruos poderosos rápidamente.

   - Uso de Imsety: Utiliza iImsety para buscar tu "King's Sarcophagus" y poder acceder a tus cartas clave sin perder ventaja en la mano.

   - Coach King Giant Trainer: Esta carta es esencial para infligir daño a tu oponente y robar cartas adicionales, lo que te ayuda a mantener el control del juego y a reponer tu mano constantemente.

 

Gestión de Recursos:

   - Optimización de la Mano: Asegúrate de tener siempre cartas útiles en tu mano para poder activar efectos como el de "Bigfoot" o "Rainbow".

 

Estrategias de Invocación:

   - Uso de XYZ y Enlace: Aprovecha las invocaciones XYZ para acceder a monstruos poderosos como "Zombie Vampire" o "IP Masquerena". Estos te permiten controlar el campo y manejar las cartas de tu oponente con eficacia.

   - Sinergia de Monstruos Horus: Mantén a tus monstruos Horus en el campo para maximizar sus efectos y asegurar la posibilidad de traerlos de vuelta si son destruidos.

 

Juegos Tempranos y Tardíos:

   - Juego Temprano: En los primeros turnos, céntrate en establecer tu campo y buscar las cartas clave para tus combos. Usa Genta y Rainbow para buscar y preparar tus puertas y monstruos.

   - Juego Tardío: En fases avanzadas del juego, aprovecha los recursos acumulados y los efectos de invocación de tus monstruos para presionar a tu oponente y buscar el OTK (One Turn Kill) si es posible.

 

Adaptación y Flexibilidad:

   - Variación de Estrategias: Experimenta con diferentes versiones del mazo para encontrar la combinación que mejor se adapte a tu estilo de juego y al meta actual. Considera cartas adicionales como "Zeus" para situaciones específicas.

   - Adaptación en el Campo: Según el desarrollo del juego, ajusta tus estrategias para maximizar el uso de tus cartas. No dudes en cambiar de plan si las circunstancias lo requieren.

 

Protección y Control:

   - Protección del Rey Sark: Mantén a "King's Sarcophagus" en el campo para asegurar que tus monstruos Horus puedan regresar si son destruidos. Esto proporciona una capa adicional de protección y control sobre el campo.

   - Interacción con el Oponente: Usa cartas como "Sillva" para controlar la mano del oponente y limitar sus opciones. Esta estrategia puede ser clave para mantener la ventaja y asegurar la victoria.

 

Siguiendo estas estrategias y ajustando tu mazo según tus experiencias y el meta del juego, podrás maximizar el rendimiento de tu mazo "Dark World Horus" y asegurar victorias consistentes en tus partidas.

El mazo de Dark World Fiend Smith tiene una serie de estrategias clave que se pueden emplear para maximizar su efectividad. Aquí tienes un resumen de las mejores tácticas basadas en la transcripción del video:

 

Uso temprano de Genta:

   - Descartar a Genta para agregar rápidamente la "Puerta del Mundo Oscuro" al juego, lo que te permitirá empezar a rotar cartas y activar otros efectos del mazo.

 

Cadena de efectos:

   - Aprovecha la secuencia de activación de efectos al descartar y agregar cartas, como la cadena de efectos entre Genta, Graffa y Snee, para maximizar los beneficios de robar y descartar cartas.

 

Activación de Puerta del Mundo Oscuro:

   - Utiliza "Puerta del Mundo Oscuro" para descartar y desterrar cartas como Graffa y Genta. Esto te permite robar cartas adicionales y activar efectos en cadena, permitiendo la reutilización de los recursos en tu cementerio.

 

Uso de Arcoíris y Lucient:

   - Descartar a Arcoíris para agregar a Lucient, aumentando tu presencia en el tablero con monstruos de alto nivel, lo que facilita las invocaciones y combinaciones posteriores.

 

Estrategias de combinación y fusión:

   - Utiliza el "Catalyst Zaman" para descartar a Arcoíris, invocarlo y luego usar su efecto para agregar monstruos adicionales a tu mano, como Plateado, incrementando la presión en el tablero.

   - Considera invocar monstruos de fusión como "Dark World Overlord Graffa" y "Fiend Smith Fusion Monsters" para aumentar tus opciones de negaciones y destrucción en el campo del oponente.

 

Uso del efecto de Fiend Smith:

   - Aprovecha la capacidad de "Fiend Smith" para agregar "Tractus" y luego usar "Tractus" para traer monstruos adicionales al tablero, permitiendo una mayor manipulación del campo y preparación para invocaciones de rango o fusión.

 

Manipulación del Cementerio y Reciclaje:

   - Utiliza efectos que permiten reciclar cartas del cementerio de vuelta al mazo, como el efecto de la "Secuencia" para recuperar recursos importantes y mantener la presión constante en el juego.

 

Estrategias de Invocación Xyz y Enlace:

   - Invoca monstruos Xyz como "DDD High Wave King Caesar" para aprovechar sus efectos de robo y descarte adicionales.

   - Usa monstruos de enlace como "IP Masquerena" para establecer una defensa sólida y permitir jugadas adicionales durante el turno del oponente.

 

Maximizar Ventaja de Mano:

   - Siempre busca mantener una buena ventaja de mano mediante los efectos de robo y descarte de tus cartas clave, como "Graffa" y "Rainbow", para tener siempre opciones disponibles.

 

Protección y Negaciones:

    - Utiliza monstruos de fusión como "Fiend Smith DARA" y otros grandes monstruos fusionados para proporcionar múltiples negaciones y protección en el tablero, aumentando tu capacidad de respuesta a las jugadas del oponente.

 

Implementar estas estrategias en tus partidas con el mazo Dark World Fiend Smith debería ayudarte a optimizar tus jugadas y aprovechar al máximo el potencial de las cartas disponibles en este arquetipo.

deck_name: GOAT Structure Deck: Spirit of Cerebrus - Molten Beastdown
deck_excerpt: Rescue Cat and Little Chimera package deck in the stye of a structure, for under $15.
deck_description:
A volcano of power has been brewing, and now, burning beasts have erupted onto the field. Can you harness this energy, or will you burn up in its infernal fury? Introducing the "Spirit of Cerberus" GOAT Format Structure Deck – a masterful blend of Beast Beatdown and Pyro Aggro strategies, creating a formidable force ready to scorch the competition. With the dynamic "Rescue Cat" and "Little Chimera" package, your monsters get the boost they need to reign supreme on the battlefield.

Harness the ferocious might of both beasts and flames as you delve into a deck designed for destruction and dominance. The heart of this deck lies in its ability to combine raw brute strength with explosive volcanic energy, setting the stage for epic duels where only the strongest will survive.

  • Beastly Brute Force: Utilize "Twinheaded Beast" to unleash devastating attacks. With two "Poison Fangs" and "Molten Destruction" in play, you can deal a blistering 6800 damage in a single turn. Amplify the onslaught to 8800 damage when you execute the "Rescue Cat" package flawlessly.
  • Pyro Aggression: Overwhelm your opponent with volcanic energy using powerful Pyro monsters like "Gaia Soul the Combustible Collective" and "Inferno".
  • Strategic Synergy: Leverage the synergy between "Rescue Cat" and "Little Chimera" to maximize your damage output and dominate the duel.
  • Classic Power: Includes the full set of 4 Inpachi cards and the legendary "Flame Cerebrus", one of the oldest cards in the game.

Bonus Cards: 1x Flame Cerebrus 1x Inpachi 1x Blazing Inpachi 1x Charcoal Inpachi 1x Woodborg Inpachi

deck_description: (This is a Master Duel Deck) haha clown

Generaiders work as a factastic grindy rank 9 engine. The T.G. support gives the Deck a 1.5 card combo full board, leaving room for other engines. The Runick cards act as non engine, extenders, or a draw/discard engine as needed.

While it has a few garnets, with 42 cards, you will see good hands far more than bad ones, and there is always room to combo off (so long as your opponent  doesn't draw 3 hand traps).

This is the most recent version of Generaider that I have cooked up. I have been trying to make this deck viable for years. This is the closest I have seen this Deck come to playability, and while there are liberties here which are only here because of the current format, the over all list still holds.

Diabellstar Snake-Eye Fire King  / Central America WCQ 2024 Top 32
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Sergio Ethan Vera Briseno

Tournament: Central America WCQ 2024 – June 21st 2024

Placement: Top 32

Why does this work out...

Hello, welcome!

This deck focuses on the big boss gizmeks hiting the field and controlling the board whilst using the fact that the appliancer monsters are machines with equal ATK and DEF. It's meh at best however the shining star of the deck is Gizmek Uka, the Festive Fox of Fecundity which allows us to essentially search our deck for any gizmek monster with the same attribute as an opponents monster. Also, appliancer can set up a few good boards with a cool two card combo and, with some changes, can FTK you opponent.This deck plays alot of hand traps too, about 11 including Gizmek Uka, the Festive Fox of Fecundity, so ... thats good I suppose???

For the appliancer engine you play:

    - 3 Appliancer Socketroll 

    - 3 Appliancer Copybokkle 

    - 0 or 2 Appliancer Breakerbuncle

    - 1 or 2 Appliancer Celtopus 

    - 2 Appliancer Laundry Dragon 

    - 1 Appliancer Propelion 

    - 1 Appliancer Vacculephant 

    - 3 Appliancer Electrilyrical World 

    - 3 Appliancer Reuse 

    - 1 Appliancer Test or 1 Appliancer Conversion 

The applincer stuff allows you to make a 3 (or 4) negate Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess which then can go into a massive Accesscode Talker, or can FTK using some phantom knights cards and Raider's Knight with Arc Rebellion Xyz Dragon to punch for 8100 of damage. They also work well with the gizmek cards mostly because they're machines with equal ATK and DEF however what makes them work well with eachother is that Appliancer Socketroll can proc Gizmek Uka, the Festive Fox of Fecundity as it summons from the main deck and Gizmek Naganaki, the Sunrise Signaler can also be treated as another 3 copies of Appliancer Socketroll being able to normal summon itself then tributeing it for a machine monster with an equal ATK and DEF which happens to be the stats of an Appliancer Socketroll.

In addition, it's manditory to play:

    - 1 Codebreaker Zero Day 

    - 1 Codebreaker Virus Swordsman 

    - 1 Codebreaker Virus Berserker 

These not only allow us to extend our link plays by being a massive +3 in card economy but can also facilitate a short but, not so, sweet FTK stratagy. Alongside the gizmek cards this could be a very fun control/FTK deck you can play (if you change the ratios to be more consistant with that).

For the gizmeks you play:

    - 1 Gizmek Okami, the Dreaded Deluge Dragon 

    - 1 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag 

    - 1 Gizmek Orochi, the Serpentron Sky Slasher 

    - 3 Gizmek Uka, the Festive Fox of Fecundity 

    - 3 Gizmek Makami, the Ferocious Fanged Fortress 

    - 3 Gizmek Naganaki, the Sunrise Signaler 

These cards do two seperate things depending on what role they have:

  -The boss monsters special summon themselvs to the field and break open boards to make way for any FTK stratagies or to annoy your opponent                because all their cards are either in the banishment or the GY.

  -The other gizmek cards allow us to search our deck for materials we may need or in the case of Gizmek Makami, the Ferocious Fanged Fortress        un-banish our previously banished cards (usually by Gizmek Orochi, the Serpentron Sky Slasher) incase it gets destroyed whilst being extra                material for any links.

Other engines you can play are:

    - The phanton knights

        - These allow you to FTK using a very small engine taking up only 3 main deck slots and 3 extra deck slots, those cards being:

        - The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak 

        - The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots 

        - The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine 

        - The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche 

        - Raider's Knight 

        - Arc Rebellion Xyz Dragon 

    - The main combo is:

    - Appliancer Socketroll/[Appliancer Socketroll/Gizmek Naganaki, the Sunrise Signaler] + Appliancer Electrilyrical World 

    [ Gizmek Naganaki, the Sunrise Signaler summon itself > tribute Gizmek Naganaki, the Sunrise Signaler to summon out a Appliancer Socketroll]      activate Appliancer Electrilyrical World to add whichever one you don't have ( Appliancer Socketroll or Appliancer Copybokkle) > once you have      a Appliancer Socketroll on field, Appliancer Copybokkle effect target Appliancer Socketroll; special summon it with the name of Appliancer                Socketroll > Appliancer Socketroll triger; summon another Appliancer Socketroll from deck > link both Appliancer Socketrolls into a Appliancer        Celtopus > Appliancer Electrilyrical World will trigger; add a Appliancer Socketroll from your GY to your hand > Appliancer Socketroll can                special summon itself since you controll an appliancer monster > link both of the level 1 applinacer monsters into Codebreaker Virus Swordsman,            making sure that it's co-linked with Appliancer Celtopus (yes the zones do matter) > since Codebreaker Virus Swordsman is co-linked it can special      summon a Codebreaker Zero Day from your deck/hand > link both codebreaker monsters to make Codebreaker Virus Berserker underneath                 Appliancer Celtopus > Codebreaker Virus Berserker will trigger to summon back both codebreaker monsters to zones link monsters point to > link         Appliancer Celtopus and Codebreaker Virus Swordsman into The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche > The Phantom Knights of Rusty                Bardiche effect sending The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak to the GY, setting The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine > banish The              Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak adding The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots > special summon The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots >            overlay both The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine and Codebreaker Zero Day for a Raider's Knight > Raider's Knight effect can detatch 1;      to stack ontop a Arc Rebellion Xyz Dragon > Arc Rebellion Xyz Dragon effect detatch 1; blanket negate all monsters on field and make it's ATK              the combined ATK of all monster on your side of the field 8100.

    -This is a very fun way to surprise your opponent by siding this in game 2 or 3 when your opponent thinks they have your stratagy down.

    - predaplants...

    - I mean they're dark monsters plus the scales could pundulum summon your Appliancer Socketroll and this does have some cool applications and            some powerfull end boards but I don't think this is worth it...

     The combo is:

      Both predaplant pendulum monsters ( Predaplant Bufolicula and Predaplant Triantis) + an Appliancer Socketroll/ Appliancer Copybokkle  +             Appliancer Electrilyrical World + a monster discard (omg a 4.5 card combo)

      Set the scales with both predaplant monsters > activate Appliancer Electrilyrical World, add the one you don't haveAppliancer Copybokkle                  effect target Appliancer Socketroll; special summon it with the name of Appliancer  Socketroll > Appliancer Socketroll triger; summon                          another Appliancer Socketroll from deck > link both Appliancer Socketrolls into a Appliancer Celtopus > Appliancer Electrilyrical World will              trigger; add a Appliancer Socketroll from your GY to your hand > Appliancer Socketroll can special summon itself since you controll an                          appliancer    monster > link both of the level 1 applinacer monsters into Codebreaker Virus Swordsman, making sure that it's co-linked                              with Appliancer  Celtopus (yes the zones do matter) > since Codebreaker Virus Swordsman is co-linked it can special summon a Codebreaker            Zero Day from your deck/hand > link both codebreaker monsters to make Codebreaker Virus Berserker underneath Appliancer                                      Celtopus > Codebreaker Virus Berserker will trigger to summon back both codebreaker monsters to zones link monsters point to > link all the                  codebreaker monsters into an Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess (mind you this is 10 summons in Nibiru, the Primal Being will allready be on the              board) > Predaplant Bufolicula activate it's effect fusioning both the scaled monsters into a Predaplant Ambulomelides > chain the effects of                 Predaplant Bufolicula, Predaplant Triantis and Predaplant Ambulomelides resolving them doing:

      Predaplant Bufolicula: adding Predaplant Triantis to hand

     Predaplant Ambulomelides: adding Predaplant Bufolicula to hand

     Predaplant Triantis: placing a predator counter on Appliancer Celtopus (use this to chain block)

     reset the scales (like a randon fusion appeared on to your field)  > Predaplant  Ambulomelides tribute itself for a Predaplant Ophrys                               Scorpio > Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio effect discard a monster; summon a Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra > Predaplant Darlingtonia                         Cobra effect; add a Polymerization to your hand > fusion summon Greedy Venom Fusion Dragon using Predaplant Triantis and Predaplant                 Darlingtonia Cobra (optional MD only > you can then link Appliancer Celtopus and Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio into Predaplant Verte Anaconda         and activate that to go into Predaplant Dragostapelia) 

     This puts up a good board that can interact with your opponent quite a bit also it dosn't use your normal summon effect unlike pure appliancer                      soooooo... adventure engine anyone? (if you do Thunder Dragon Colossus anyone?.. no. okay then.)

Extra Deck:

It's mainly filled with extra-deck-filler with cards like:

    - I:P Masquerena 

    - Knightmare Unicorn 

    - Knightmare Phoenix

    - Relinquished Anima 

    - Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess 

However the appliancer link-1s can be used to controll the board quite nicely:

    - Appliancer Laundry Dragon, when attacked or attacking you can destroy that monster then burn your opponent for it's attack (not co-linked)

    - Appliancer Vacculephant, destruction removal + attacking directly

    - Appliancer Propelion, make an opponents monster 0 ATK

You can play the others for a more pure build but I feel that they don't work well with the gizmek controll-type stratagy. Also you play the xyz for 2 board wipes with Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.

Overall this deck can be played in a veriaty of ways and I think that it could be good, emphasis on the could, all that said it's a fun deck to play and feels really rewarding when (more like if) you win against a deck like snake-eye.

Thats all you need to know REMEMBER this isn't the best oronly way to play appliancer so change the deck as you wish and as allways stay safe and have fun (: !

I'm going to do a deck that was verry good against tearlaments and one of my personal favourites ... good ol' melffy spright, see you there.

deck_description: Goat Format Water Aggro Deck. NOT MY DECK! Credits in the youtube link.

First GOAT deck I've made, a blend of two deck ideas: Chaos Control and Ben Kei OTK. This was made using the cards I have at home in bulk. All the Ben Kei stall cards (gravity bind, level limit area B) are removed in favor of some strong tech choices.

Ben Kei, I like it in edison format but like in all formats this deck has it's flaws specially since it requires so many cards on the field to succeed, after Isolde got banned I've been cracking my head to make this playable and I think I'am on a good track but still needs improvement, please help me improve this deck:


* The goal of the deck is to get Ben Kei into the GY as soon as possible to be brought when you have the equips to finish off your opponent.

If you have Mage Power, Clarent and brought back Ben Kei with D.D.R is gg as long as you do not encounter any disruptions.

To get Ben Kei into the GY you can do so with Armageddon Knight or Foolish burial to send him directly from the deck, drawing him first hand is not convenient, also in order to get Armageddon knight out as quick as possible you could use Summoner Monk or ROTA

* Summoner Monk: It initiates the combo and can have synergy with the Cursed Bamboo Sword triggering the eff when discarded, it is the normal summon of the deck, his main weakness are hand traps, if you discard an equip spell do not worry as they can be brought back.

* Revolution Synchron: It can be used on hand to make the Power Tool Dragon to bring out more equips, this could be extenders or essential equips to finish off your opponent it depends on what do you have at the moment on hand and field, once this card is in the grave it can be brought back to do more Synchros

* Corageus Crimson Chavalier Bradamante: Best Equip searcher even though it equips immediately when it searches this can be very useful if you need another equip for the finishing combo or if you need a bamboo or Durendal to extend your play

* Divine Sword Phoenix Blade: In order to pull out Ben Kei from the afterlife you need to first get him to tha banished zone with Divine Sword Phoenix blade this can be done. with cards like bradamante and Foolish goods this card can be taken out faster from the deck but the combo goes a bit slow with cars like roland that brings it in the end phase.

* Since the deck is such a blind second deck going first and build a good field tends to be a challenge and going second you would have to play around all the disruptions I need to improve my comboes.

Extra Deck:
* Many Cards in the extra deck go for their synergy with equips, warrios and FIRE monsters

If you read til this point thank you any advice and comments are well received, have a nice one :D

deck_excerpt: gentlemen's agreement to not use the sideboard
deck_description:
This is a H.A.T. format Bujin build with a very toxic sideboard. Bujin is a control list with the potential to make explosive OTKs happen. The key piece of the deck is Yamato, which searches for any Bujin monster during the end phase and then discards a Bujin monster. This engine allows you to fill your hand with handtraps (Crane, Mikazuchi), while at the same time stacking your GY with protection (Hare, Turtle) or removal (Quilin). 

The extra deck consists of a staple rank 4 toolbox, and the Bujintei monsters. Susanowo is the main component, with a search and the ability to attack all monsters. Kagutshushi is very strong protection, allowing you to save any Bujin beast-warrior monster.

Always remember that this deck, like B.A., discriminates. The Bujin beasts cannot be saved by each other or Kagutsushi, only the beast-warriors can.

deck_excerpt: My Psy-Frame deck using the new Primoredial cards
deck_description: My Psy-Frame deck using the new Primoredial cards

I have been building on this deck since the structure deck came out, but I still have not found the ideal composition.

The idea is to use cards like Despian Tragedy, Tri-brigade Mercourier, and Springans Kit to generate an advantage by using the Banishment. This is combined with a Gren Maju package, using Necroface, Allure of Darkness, and Bystial Baldrake to dump cards in the Banishment quicker. 

In an ideal scenario, the Bystial package would be bigger and there would be more copies of Branded Opening and Super Polymerization. But those cards are expensive. I do wonder if I should add a Blazing Cartisia, the Virtuous.

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Creator: Pakawat Pamornsut

Tournament: Indianapolis WCQ Regional – June 23rd 2024

Placement: Top 8

This deck focuses on bringing out Zaborg the Mega Monarch and dumping as many cards from the extra deck as possible in the GY. 

The main combo is tribute summon Zaborg and either destroy itself or a Prime Monarch on the field with his mandatory effect. The rest of the deck is just monarch basics.

The Witch of the Black Forest and Fusion Deployment combo is a try-out, but I have some problems with it. While Witch does search every piece in this deck, it only counts as one tribute. I have seen other lists run Space Connector, but I am thinking about trying out a Sky Striker Ace - Roze and a Pillar of the Future - Cyanos. Update will follow.

This Beetrooper list aims to go second, spamming the field after clearing it with powerful boardwipes such as Lightning Storm and Evenly Matched.

The main starters are Beetrooper Scout Buggy and Cyclos the Circular Sprite. With Almiraj you can also use Resonance Insect as a starter, but this requires follow-up. Most of the time you will climb the link ladder, with the support of the Ragnaraika toolkit, but you can also fusion summon Beetrooper Absolute Hercules for a defensive option.

deck_excerpt: Get your gamble on, and mill mill mill your way to Masters 1 with Tearlament Horus!
deck_description:
Nearly two years after its inception in Power of the Elements in the OCG/TCG, Tearlaments continues to be the metagame graveyard powerhouse! Historically being the strongest Yugioh deck of all time, Tearlaments has weathered the many banlists that targeted it, and it still remains a tier 1 meta threat to this day - especially on Masterduel ladder!

With the Horus cards now part of Masterduel, Tearlaments have another way to mill cards to the GY with The Zombie Vampire, easily accessible by the level 8 bodies that Horus monsters provide. Get your gamble on, and mill mill mill your way to Masters 1 with Horus Tearlaments!

Tearlaments' gameplan is to mill as much as possible to trigger graveyard effects. Like every Tearlaments strategy, this deck aims to mill as much as possible and gain beneficial effects from those mills. The reliance on mills makes this strategy unpredictable and luck dependant, meaning that there are hardly any straightforward combos. 

There are no straightforward "combos" for Tearlaments due to the random nature of the deck. Combos are hand/mill dependent - leaving the rest of the game up to the duelists individual skill, decision making and mental fortitude (that's the Tearlaments is considered as a difficult to pilot deck). Tearlaments are also infamous for requiring a great deal of skill, since the pilot has to be aware of the various interactions they have in the GY and the amount of cards left in their main deck. 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: fusion of fairies and machine play in harmony for some of the biggest end boards
deck_description:
Welcome to my very budget deck that i believe is very high rogue in this snake-eyes format.

This deck come from the fact i couldn't afford 1st movement solo for UK nats.

the biggest advantage of this deck is the 12 to 15 non-engine space, and the massive end board.

the biggest draw to the deck is the high ceiling and cards being a soft once per turn, allows the player to loop resources for follow-up plays. the deck naturely has build in onminegate, and resolving ostinato results in a almost unbreakable board backed with non-engine, and this deck does lose to linging effect like dimensional barrier since ABC is a special summon not classified as a fusion summon, weird yugioh rulings.

If you are a big ABC, i would highly recommend the build especially with the new support coming out with the new sets, the lock into light monster work with the melodious cards, as they are light fusion, and the melodious light lock pendulum summoning is in prefect tandem with ABC cards. the extra deck is never going to feel big enough, especially with option for rank 4, like bagooska against shifter deck and dweller for graveyard heavy deck, addition synchro plays and another disruptive link plays. 

i hope you have fun looking and exploring this deck potential.

deck_description:
This Deck features many ways to get Blue-Eyes out of the hand, such as Keeper of Dragon Magics effect or Trade In. Jet Dragon and Keeper of the Shrine stick to the board to stall for a combo. Sage and Master search and recycle Effect Veiler.

Combos

Open with Sage with Eyes of Blue and Dictator of D.,Special summon Dictator of D., Normal summon Sage with Eyes of Blue, add White Stone of Legend, Discard White Stone of Legend to special summon Blue-Eyes, add a Blue-Eyes White Dragon from deck to your hand, Synchro Summon any Lv 5 or 9.(Samsaras pretty safe, But Spirit Dragon never hurts.)

Open with Keeper of Dragon Magic and Blue Eyes White Dragon, Normal Summon Keeper and discard Blue-Eyes to get Poly, Use Keeper to special summon Blue-Eyes from the grave, Fusion summon Blue Eyes Tyrant Dragon and hope for the best.

deck_name: Winged Dragon of Ra Deck - Improved
deck_description: [BANNED AND LIMITED LIST ON YGOPRODECK NOT UPDATED: TERRAFORMING NOT BANNED, POT OF EXTRAVAGENCE NOT LIMITED]This deck is most useful if you are able to eliminate your opponent's board, and then direct attack with The Winged Dragon of Ra. To get The Winged Dragon of Ra and summon it in one turn, your goal is to get Ancient Chant to do so. Having cards like Terraforming and The True Sun God, you are able to get Ancient Chant and summon Ra in one turn. You can also do this with Millennium Revelation. A shield you can put up to stop battle damage is using Egyptian God Slime, with 3,000 attack and defense, as well it being unable to be destroyed by battle, so if set in defense mode you can put up an unbreakable shield, not counting spell/trap cards as well as monster effects. A way you can easily get Egyptian God Slime is by using Reactor Slime's effect and tributing it to get a Metal Reflect Slime, and tributing that for an Egyptian God Slime, all in one turn. Pot of Extravagance is used to get the cards you want by sacrificing the cards in your extra deck you don't need, like Salamangreat Almaraj, Knightmare Pheonix and Unicorn, Cross-Sheep, and Muddragon of the Swamp. You can put a Time-Tearing Morganite in this deck, but it is slow as you have to wait a turn for it to be useful. As well as that, Time-Tearing Morganite makes using Immortal Pheonix impossible.
This deck is 80% getting Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder onto the field using the low-level XYZ summons. The other 20% is using card effects to keep your cards from taking damage.
