deck_excerpt: A mix of Centur-Ion, Toy and White Woods. Really consistent at getting what you want.
deck_description:
My take on a 50-card pile for the newly releasing White Woods archetype.

They synergise really well with Centur-Ion, and the Toy engine allowing themselves to special summon themselves when they're sent for a White Woods effect is also just free bodies on board for I:P/S:P, or if you're desperate for the synchro material for Centur-Ion Auxila or Legatia, dependent on hand quality.

Centur-Ion in of itself as an archetype is just stupid. Synchro-ing on your opponents turn for a free calamity lock into game is ridiculous, and Stand-Up Centur-Ion!'s ability to synchro summon during your opponents turn off a special summon makes the Silvera Book of Moon effect live and very scary for your opponent to come up against.

I had also tested this deck at 43 cards, however it felt weaker than the 50-card pile. You're wanting to see either Centur-Ion or White Woods cards in hand and whilst the 43 card deck was more consistent in having full combo, the lack of hand-traps and over-reliance on setting up a board that can get you access to Calamity tipped the 50-card pile in my opinion.

The side deck is purely aimed at my locals. Please change this to your own tastes if you are copying the deck.

Your best hand is seeing Risette with a White Woods spell or trap, as they can set themselves for when you add Asteria.

Most common hand is seeing a Centur-Ion name like Trudea/Primera without the Stand-Up!

Your worst hand is just seeing pure hand traps. However that's the beauty of this 50-card pile is that whatever your dead hand is you can definitely still interact with the game.

deck_excerpt: Dragonmaids w/ an Enhanced Metalmorph engine.
deck_description:
So in Rage of the Abyss, Konami gave Bandit Keith and Joey Wheeler some legacy support, referencing their duel in "Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Monsters." The two most important monsters in the Enhanced Metalmorph engine are Metalzoa X and what I'm using in this deck: Red-Eyes Black Fullmetal Dragon.

 

REBFD has three effects. You can reveal it in your hand to set a Metalmorph trap from your Deck, and shuffle this card into your deck. Also, if your opponent activates a card or effect, you can negate the activation and inflict damage to your opponent equal to the original ATK of one of their Attack Position monsters. REBFD must first be Special Summoned by "Enhanced Metalmorph" by Tributing a Level 5 or higher Dragon.

 

You know what has exactly that, and likes to go first? Dragonmaids. Many monsters in the archetype are high-Level Dragons, and Dragonmaid Sheou in particular is an omni-negate. Once you use Sheou's negation effect and tag out into House Dragonmaid, you can Tribute her with Enhanced Metalmorph to summon REBFD. Alternatively, you can revive a Level 5 or higher Dragon with Sheou's other effect, and then tribute it with Enhanced Metalmorph for two negates on board.

 

Finally, if you can end your turn with Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres and a set Enhanced Metalmorph, you can summon a high-Level Dragon with Heavenly Spheres's effect after tributing Spheres to bounce an opponent's card, and then activate Enhanced Metamorph to get a boss monster out. 

 

As for this deck's name, it's called "J-Metalmorph" in reference to Japanese metal. I just started listening to Babymetal, among other bands and artists, and Babymetal is my favorite J-Metal band.

deck_excerpt: OTK com a carta Fada da Injeção Também serve para o Master Duel.
deck_description: Apresentarei a vocês um Deck Anti-Meta centrado na carta Fada da Injeção, incluindo também a carta "Jowgen the Spiritualist" que impede qualquer jogador de realizar invocações especiais, juntamente com a carta mágica de equipamento "Moon Mirror Shield", que proporciona um aumento de 100 de ATK para o monstro equipado em relação ao do oponente durante a batalha. Outra combinação presente neste deck é a utilização do monstro "Banisher of the Radiance" em conjunto com a carta mágica contínua "Gravekeeper's Servant". O efeito do "Banisher" bane todas as cartas que seriam enviadas para o cemitério, enquanto o "Gravekeeper" força o oponente a enviar uma carta do topo do deck para o cemitério antes de atacar. Dessa forma, o combo impede que o oponente envie cartas para o cemitério devido ao efeito do "Banisher", impossibilitando-o de atacar. Por último, vamos falar sobre o combo principal envolvendo a Fada da Injeção, a carta mágica de equipamento "Unstable Evolution" e a carta mágica normal "Secret Pass to The Treasures". Vamos explicar o processo passo a passo. Primeiramente, você deve invocar a Fada da Injeção. Em seguida, ative a carta mágica normal "Secret Pass to The Treasures" e equipe o monstro com a carta "Unstable Evolution". Ao pagar os 2000 pontos de vida, seus pontos de vida ficarão abaixo dos do oponente, fazendo com que o Ataque original da Fada da Injeção se torne 2400 + os 3000 pontos de bônus de ataque concedidos pelo seu próprio efeito, totalizando 5400 ATK. Por seguir esse processo passo a passo e ativar primeiro a "Secret Pass to The Treasures", seu monstro poderá atacar diretamente o oponente causando 5400 pontos de dano.

deck_description: Apresentarei a vocês um Deck Anti-Meta centrado na carta Fada da Injeção, incluindo também a carta "Jowgen the Spiritualist" que impede qualquer jogador de realizar invocações especiais, juntamente com a carta mágica de equipamento "Moon Mirror Shield", que proporciona um aumento de 100 de ATK para o monstro equipado em relação ao do oponente durante a batalha. Outra combinação presente neste deck é a utilização do monstro "Banisher of the Radiance" em conjunto com a carta mágica contínua "Gravekeeper's Servant". O efeito do "Banisher" bane todas as cartas que seriam enviadas para o cemitério, enquanto o "Gravekeeper" força o oponente a enviar uma carta do topo do deck para o cemitério antes de atacar. Dessa forma, o combo impede que o oponente envie cartas para o cemitério devido ao efeito do "Banisher", impossibilitando-o de atacar. Por último, vamos falar sobre o combo principal envolvendo a Fada da Injeção, a carta mágica de equipamento "Unstable Evolution" e a carta mágica normal "Secret Pass to The Treasures". Vamos explicar o processo passo a passo. Primeiramente, você deve invocar a Fada da Injeção. Em seguida, ative a carta mágica normal "Secret Pass to The Treasures" e equipe o monstro com a carta "Unstable Evolution". Ao pagar os 2000 pontos de vida, seus pontos de vida ficarão abaixo dos do oponente, fazendo com que o Ataque original da Fada da Injeção se torne 2400 + os 3000 pontos de bônus de ataque concedidos pelo seu próprio efeito, totalizando 5400 ATK. Por seguir esse processo passo a passo e ativar primeiro a "Secret Pass to The Treasures", seu monstro poderá atacar diretamente o oponente causando 5400 pontos de dano.

deck_excerpt: Ice Barrier, Runick, Meta, Infinite Forbidden, Icejade, Toadally Awesome, Rogue
deck_description:
Icejade Ran Aegirine is just a free level 10 before extension plays or opt to make Coral for Mirror Mage lines. Runick cards assist with insulating the weakness of board breaking and baiting interaction that Ice Barrier can suffer from. 

Mulcharmy also considered a water for Ran Aegirine Discard Fodder. Deck has a difficult going 2nd so a strong side choice option for the deck that can get you to your Runick board breakers. 

No handtraps assist within main avoid getting Crossout creating weird siding patterns for opponent going into Game 2/3 with you opting for Droll (Could also be Nibiru/Crow depending on formats shake-up.)

Pank helps with breaking boards similar to Kashtira. One-ofs of the good floodgate Ice Barrier cards. Georgius can summon Wayne however rest are Lancea targets. 

Siding Options for Counterplay: 
Medium of the Ice Barrier: Sky Striker, Runick, Purrely
General Wayne of the Ice Barrier: Sky Striker
Raiho: Yubel,  Ritual Beast, Tenpai

These will be usually summoned off of Lancea on the first summon. For other match-ups keep in mind the floodgate effects of Revealer & Georgius. Georgius shuts off monster effects in grave which can be an answer to Fiendsmith. Revealer shuts off tribute summoning which is relevant in the Floo match-up since it shuts off all their palys. With Revealer in floo if you have a read on the match-up try to leave her on board with another name to ensure they can't start going off and the fact Lancea cannot activate in the match-up. You'll use the Icejade Ran Aegirine since it will effectively choke the deck out of their spells/field spells. 

Important to note that the 1st summon off of Lancea and its your only card/Ice Barrier related card the floodgate effects will not be active since it is not a named 'Ice Barrier' card. 

Great Match-ups: 
Tenpai
Yubel 
Voiceless Voice

Bad Match-ups: 
Purrely 
Ritual Beast 
Memento

deck_description:

Going first you can set up lvl8 XYZ for negates, maybe Light & Darkness Dragon, and maybe Vanity's Ruler. Shut out opponent from playing.

Going second, clear the enemy board as best you can, shut them out from playing as best you can, and/or go for an OTK with a Horus board.

Volcanic Shell is for discard fodder. If you discard it with King's Sarcophogus live, you can cycle more Shells into the hand for more disccard fodder!

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Creator: Duc Nguyen

Tournament: The Side Deck Remote Duel WCQ Regional – June 29th 2024

Placement: Top 8

Ice Barrier Control Deck with Kaiju Power!

This deck focuses on controlling the duel through negates, selective monster removal, and resource management. Here's a breakdown of its key features:

  • Ice Barrier Core: The core of the deck utilizes Ice Barrier monsters like Revealer, Strategist, Speaker, and Winds to search for each other, disrupt your opponent's plays, and gradually build advantage.
  • Kaiju Power: Gameciel and Moulinglacia provide strong removal options, allowing you to tribute summon powerful monsters from your opponent's deck and disrupt their strategies.
  • Hand Traps & Negates: Ash Blossom, Infinite Impermanence, and Called by the Grave offer powerful hand traps and negation effects to shut down your opponent's key plays.
  • Synchro Focus: The deck runs a healthy amount of Synchro monsters, with Trishula (both versions) acting as a versatile removal option. Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon provides strong negation and protection.
  • Recovery & Consistency: Foolish Burial and Medallion of the Ice Barrier provide graveyard manipulation and search power, ensuring you get the cards you need.
  • Flex Slots: Cards like Silent Angler offer spot removal, while Mirror Magic Master and Zuijin offer situational protection and disruption.

This deck prioritizes controlling the flow of the duel, strategically disrupting your opponent's plays and building advantage through Ice Barrier effects and resource management. With Kaiju power for unexpected removal and a Synchro toolbox for finishing the duel, this deck offers a unique and versatile control strategy.

deck_excerpt: Thunder Dragon continues to evolve - and this time it's with Horus!
deck_description:
Thunder Dragon continues to evolve - and this time it's with Horus!
 
The Horus package turbos out Zombie Vampire to simultaneously mill and summon combo pieces from deck, as well as apply pressure on established boards with high ATK and King's Sarcophagus'  non-targeting non-destroying removal. Played with the Bystial cards, and now you have a Thunder Dragon deck that can catch up to the blisteringly fast Masterduel 2024 meta!
 
If you want a thorough guide on how to play this deck, check out my article from a couple months ago by clicking here.

GLHF Duelists!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

This deck is pretty much SpankoYGO's deck from his YouTube video on the subject. The only difference is a third Solemn Judgment instead of Delinquent Duo to keep the price down. If you have DD, just replace the third Solemn. The idea of the deck is fairly simple, turbo out you Elemental Heroes and use their effects. Sanwitch and Twin-Headed can also be summoned using monsters in the deck as a backup.

deck_description:
"Above us, outlined against the brilliant sky, dragons crowded every available perching space on the Rim. And the sun made a gold of every one of them."

Through lands across, people fear the dragons. Only one could rule over such beasts, puzzeled and seperated into 5 pieces.

I got last place, statistically the event went really bad, but in the last round I probably had the most fun Ive ever had.

We played 4 rounds which I all lost.

In the last round, we only played one duel, because we got into time in my second turn (4th turn total).

Because we did a ton of mistakes and an insane back and forth we took super long, eventually I had everything of his interrupts baited and only had to do lethal, which was really hard and I ended up with 3500LP and he with 3600LP. Insanely close, Insanely fun game and I really dont care I lost at all, this entire tournament was worth it because of this one duel.

Also, because he didnt read any of my stuff correctly I was able to easily out rivalry because he thought I cant push back a monster if theres something in that zone :D.

deck_name: A King's Guide to Red Dragon Archfiend (Post-BLTR)
deck_excerpt: The Crimson King Jack Atlas has received two new toys from BLTR - Shining Star Dragon and Red Lotus King!
deck_description:
The Crimson King Jack Atlas has received two new toys from Battles of Legend: Terminal Revenge - Shining Star Dragon and Red Lotus King! 
 
First of all, Shining Star Dragon grants the deck access to a monster boardwipe during your opponent's Main Phase! Using Shining Star Dragon to "quick-synch" into the generically accessible Centur-Ion Auxilia (which happens to be a dark dragon monster) fulfills Scarred Dragon Archfiend's conditional fieldwipe! 
 
Red Lotus King, Flame Crime acts as an additional extender for the strategy, allowing Red Dragon to play past the handtraps that are all too common in this format. It also sends any normal trap from deck to GY, allowing Red Dragon to finally easily access its power array of trap cards like Red Reign (field wipe) and Time to Stand Up! (monster negate). 

Red Dragon Archfiend has 12 one card combos, and several ways to two-card combo, making the deck extremely consistent - on par with other synchro strategies like Swordsoul and P.U.N.K. This allows the strategy to fit in a whopping 18+ non-engine cards and still be playable! As a result, this deck can confidently play through minor handtraps like Ash Blossom and Impermanence while having enough gas to power through interruption. 
 
The deck also works and melds incredibly well with Bystials very much like Dragonlink or Branded, netting you additional resources, interruption, extenders, beatsticks and combo pieces. 
 
BE THE CRIMSON KING WITH RED DRAGON ARCHFIEND! ABSOLUTE POWERFORCE!!! SYNNKRROOOO SHOOOKKAAAAANNNNN!!!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING
 
This decklist is almost identical to my previous TCG Red Dragon lists - I basically made room to add in the new toys from BLTR like Shining Star Dragon and Red Lotus King. This strategy is paired up with the Bystial cards, since they support each other exceptionally well. 
 
The RED DRAGON ARCHFIEND cards comprise the main core of this deck, being 18 cards. Your 13 one card combo starters are x3 Stone Sweeper, x3 Soul Resonator, x3 Resonator Call, x3 Crimson Gaia and x1 Foolish Burial (Send Vision Resonator, search Crimson Gaia). You have 6 conditional two card combo starters and they are x3 Vision Resonator (has to be sent to GY to search Crimson Gaia, starting combo) and x3 Bone Archfiend (sends to GY Vision Resonator, searching Crimson Gaia, starting combo). 
 
The BYSTIAL cards are added as a support archetype for this strategy and they are composed of 8 cards. The Bystial cards fulfill many functions - they are resource generation, interruption, extenders, beatsticks and combo pieces. Branded Regained is also an amazing card to have in the backrow and have inherent synergy with Red Dragon Archfiend synchro monsters. In the sidedeck, you have a searchable floodgate Branded Etude which acts as a "Macro Cosmos," banishing your opponent's material for an Extra Deck/Ritual summon - this card in particular hardcounters GY centric decks like Fiendsmith and Snake-Eyes. 
 
The rest of the cards are STAPLE cards. x3 Crossout Designator is used along with its targets since Red Dragon Archfiend's vulnerability to handtraps - especially high impact ones like Nibiru and Droll. 
 
In the SIDE DECK there are many hand trapslike Droll, Ash, Imperm and Nibiru that can be sided in depending on the matchup. Archfiend Eccentrick is searchable S/T destruction with Soul Resonator, and it's best sided in when you anticipate your opponent will play floodgates when going 1st. The best cards to side out are x3 Shining Star Dragon, x3 Red Lotus King and x1 Red Reign. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Being a synchro deck, Red Dragon Archfiend is inherently combo-focused while being a highly aggressive beatdown strategy. With only one card, Red Dragon Archfiend can set up gigantic boards with many interruptions or generate massive ATK with board clearing potential to OTK your opponent. This strategy features several combos, they are resilient and can pivot to another direction depending on the gamestate and available extenders (For example, this deck can play through high impact handtraps like Nibiru, or if certain chokepoints like Red Rising Dragon and Crimson Resonator are negated/interrupted).
 
With the new cards like Shining Star Dragon and Red Lotus King, the combos remain the same - the only difference is that this deck now has additional extenders to power through plays since thats what the new BLTR cards are, extenders. 
 
 This strategy has many combos, but I'll just feature the three I like to use. 
 
Here is the deck's bread-and-butter 1 card combo: 
 
Crimson Gaia = Bystial Dispater (Monster negate or destroy) + Hot Red Dragon Archfiend (Omni-negate any card on opponent's field) + Red Zone (Targeted destuction, summons Dark Dragon Synchro from banished) + Crimson Gaia (follow-up search and summons Red Dragon Archfiend if a monster is destroyed) + Soul Resonator in GY (destruction protection) + Bone Archfiend in GY (follow-up) + Synkron Resonator (follow-up).
  1. Activate Crimson Gaia. Search Soul Resonator. 
  2. Normal summon Soul Resonator. Search Bone Archfiend. 
  3. Special summon Bone Archfiend from hand by sending a card from hand/field to GY. (For a true 1 card combo, you'd send Crimson Gaia, but typically you have other cards in hand to send since it is ideal to keep Crimson Gaia on field). 
  4. Activate Bone Archfiend's level modification effect targeting Soul Resonator reducing it's level by 1 making level 2. Send from deck to GY Crimson Resonator. (If Crimson Resonator is already in GY, send Uvualoop instead). 
  5. Synchro summon Red Rising Dragon using Bone Archfiend + Soul Resonator. 
  6. Red Rising Dragon summons from GY Crimson Resonator. 
  7. Activate Crimson Resonator's effect to summon Vision Resonator and Synkron Resonator from deck. 
  8. Synchro summon Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Crimson Resonator + Red Rising Dragon. 
  9. Synchro summon Bystial Dispater using Scarred Dragon Archfiend + Vision Resonator. 
  10. CL1 Vision Resonator to search Red Zone, CL2 Scarred Dragon Archfiend to special summon (counts as synchro summon) Red Dragon Archfiend from Extra Deck.
  11. Synchro summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend using Red Dragon Archfiend + Synkron Resonator. 
  12. Activate Synkron Resonator's effect to add from GY a resonator from GY (Soul Resonator for follow-up next turn or Vision Resonator tuner extender). 
  13. Summon any other extenders, summon additional Dark Synchro Dragon monsters (Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend can negate S/T during battle phase, like Evenly Matched or summon another Scarred Dragon since it floats and is "Red Dragon Archfiend" on the field turning on Red Zone). Set your spells/traps, especially Red Zone. 
Even if your opponent manages to clear your entire field, your GY is set up with Bone Archfiend and your hand has Soul Resonator + more so you can repeat the same thing next turn. I'd say this deck's combo potential, resource generation and explosive power is comparable to Dragonlink! 
 
Here is what to do if you've been Nibiru'd. This requires extenders in the form of Bone Archfiend and any Bystial. 
 
HELP! (I'VE BEEN NIBIRU'D!) Crimson Gaia + Bystial + Bone Archfiend = Bystial Dispater (Monster negate or destroy) + Scarred Dragon Archfiend (Presence on-field turns on Red Zone, floats into OG Red Dragon Archfiend), Red Zone (Targeted destuction, summons Dark Dragon Synchro from banished) + Crimson Gaia (follow-up search and summons Red Dragon Archfiend if a monster is destroyed) + Soul Resonator in GY (destruction protection) + Bone Archfiend in GY (follow-up) + Synkron Resonator (follow-up).
  1. Activate Crimson Gaia. Search Soul Resonator. 
  2. Normal summon Soul Resonator. Search Obsessive Uvualoop. 
  3. Special summon Bone Archfiend from hand by sending a card from hand/field to GY. (For a true 1 card combo, you'd send Crimson Gaia, but typically you have other cards in hand to send since it is ideal to keep Crimson Gaia on field). 
  4. Activate Bone Archfiend's level modification effect targeting Soul Resonator reducing it's level by 1 making level 2. Send from deck to GY Crimson Resonator. (If Crimson Resonator is already in GY, send Uvualoop instead). 
  5. Synchro summon Red Rising Dragon using Bone Archfiend + Soul Resonator. 
  6. Red Rising Dragon summons from GY Crimson Resonator. 
  7. Activate Crimson Resonator's effect to summon Vision Resonator and Synkron Resonator from deck. (AT THIS POINT, TYPICALLY OPPONENTS NIBIRU SINCE THIS IS THE 5TH SUMMON)
  8. CL1 Synkron Resonator to add Vision Resonator back to hand, CL2 Vision Resonator to search Red Zone. 
  9. Special summon Bystial, banishing Crimson Resonator from GY. 
  10. Special summon Vision Resonator from hand, since you control a level 5 or higher monster (the Bystial). 
  11. Special summon Uvualoop from hand, banishing Red Rising Dragon in GY. 
  12. Synchro summon Bystial Dis Pater using Bystial + Uvualoop. 
  13. Activate Bystial Dis Pater's effect to special summon from banished Red Rising Dragon. 
  14. Synchro summon Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Vision Resonator + Red Rising Dragon. 
  15. Summon any other extenders, summon additional Dark Synchro Dragon monsters (Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend can negate S/T during battle phase, like Evenly Matched or summon another Scarred Dragon since it floats and is "Red Dragon Archfiend" on the field turning on Red Zone). Set your spells/traps, especially Red Zone. 
The endboard isn't as good as the first combo since you've been interrupted by Nibiru, but it's more or less the same! Everything is present except for Hot Red Dragon Archfiend's on-field omni-negate. 

One of the best endboards, featuring Bystial Lubellion and the one card combo: 

Bystial Lubellion + Crimson Gaia = Bystial Dispater (Monster negate or destroy) + Hot Red Dragon Archfiend (Omni-negate any card on opponent's field) + Scarred Dragon Archfiend (Presence on-field turns on Red Zone, floats into OG Red Dragon Archfiend) + Red Zone (Targeted destuction, summons Dark Dragon Synchro from banished) + Crimson Gaia (follow-up search and summons Red Dragon Archfiend if a monster is destroyed) + Soul Resonator in GY (destruction protection) + Bone Archfiend in GY (follow-up) + Synkron Resonator (follow-up) + Branded Beast (Targeted destruction) + Branded Regained (+1 draw when a card is banished, summon Bystial from GY).
  1. Activate Crimson Gaia. Search Soul Resonator. 
  2. Normal summon Soul Resonator. Search Bone Archfiend. 
  3. Special summon Bone Archfiend from hand by sending a card from hand/field to GY. (For a true 1 card combo, you'd send Crimson Gaia, but typically you have other cards in hand to send since it is ideal to keep Crimson Gaia on field). 
  4. Activate Bone Archfiend's level modification effect targeting Soul Resonator reducing it's level by 1 making level 2. Send from deck to GY Crimson Resonator. (If Crimson Resonator is already in GY, send Uvualoop instead). 
  5. Synchro summon Red Rising Dragon using Bone Archfiend + Soul Resonator. 
  6. Red Rising Dragon summons from GY Crimson Resonator. 
  7. Activate Crimson Resonator's effect to summon Vision Resonator and Synkron Resonator from deck. 
  8. Synchro summon Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Crimson Resonator + Red Rising Dragon. 
  9. Activate Bystial Lubellion's effect to search for Bystial Saronir. 
  10. Activate Bystial Saronir's effect to summon itself banishing Crimson Resonator from GY. 
  11. Summon Lubellion from GY tributing Scarred Dragon Archfiend. 
  12. Activate Scarred Dragon Archfriend's effect to special summon (counts as synchro summon) Red Dragon Archfiend from Extra Deck.
  13. Activate Lubellion's effect to place Branded Beast on your backrow. 
  14. Synchro summon Bystial Dispater using Bystial Lubellion + Vision Resonator. 
  15. Vision Resonator searches Red Zone since it was sent to GY. 
  16. Synchro summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend using Red Dragon Archfiend + Synkron Resonator. 
  17. Activate Synkron Resonator's effect to add from GY a resonator from GY (Soul Resonator for follow-up next turn or Vision Resonator tuner extender). 
  18. Synchro summon a second Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Bystial Saronir + Crimson Resonator. 
  19. Activate Saronir's effect in the GY since it left the field. Send Branded Regained to the GY. 
  20. Summon any other extenders, summon additional Dark Synchro Dragon monsters (Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend can negate S/T during battle phase, like Evenly Matched or summon another Scarred Dragon since it floats and is "Red Dragon Archfiend" on the field turning on Red Zone). Set your spells/traps, especially Red Zone. 
  21. In the End Phase, Branded Beast places Branded Regained on your backrow. 
As you can see, there are many combos and variants in the Red Dragon Archfiend deck. There are more combos than listed in this strategy guide, but I only featured three. I suggest you check out other Youtube videos, practice for yourself, and cook your own playstyles! There is so much complexity and potential that this powerful strategy can now do!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Good cards to consider for the side deck that this deck can abuse is Eradicator Epidemic Virus (and the other virus cards), since it's an insta-win vs. certain decks.
  • Red Dragon Archfiend's usual endboard can negate Dark Ruler No More and Forbidden Droplet (if they didn't send a trap)! When your opponent activates Dark Ruler/Droplet, CL2 Red Zone to pop a card, then CL3 Hot Red Dragon Archfiend's effect to negate the card. Pretty snazzy eh? Not every deck can use a monster to negate Dark Ruler/Droplet!
  • Try to leave Soul Resonator in the GY after your combo, it is destruction protection while you control any synchro monster that mentions Red Dragon Archfiend!
  • Try to set up Banishement with a card so that Bystial Dispater can at least use it's destruction effect! Sometimes depending on your cards Bystial Dispater's destroy/negation effect won't be live. The best cards to set up the banished piles are Bystials and Obsessive Uvualoop. 
  • Obsessive Uvualoop is an incredible extender in this deck. It's also searchable as part of this deck's combo (for example, if you already have Crimson Resonator, you can search for Uvualoop). This card can banish multiple synchro monsters at the end of the regular combo so that Dispater can summon them from the banished pile, while setting up Dispater's destroy/negation! 
  • Red Dragon Archfiend is a surprisingly grindy deck. If your opponent manages to clear your entire field, you can easily recover your set-up given that your GY, banished pile and hand still remain after your initial combo lines. Red Zone summons Dark Dragon Synchros from Banishment (even Dis Pater!) Dis Pater also summons from Banishment. Bone Archfiend will be in the GY to kickstart your combo again. Obsessive Uvualoop summons itself by banishing synchros. Branded Regained summons Bystials from the GY. 
  • When siding out in games 2/3, take out varying quantities of Shining Star Dragon and Red Lotus King as needed.  
  • You have searchable spell/trap destruction in your Side Deck - Archfiend Eccentric. Side it in if you think your opponent will play floodgates with your normal summoned Soul Resonator! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING COMMENTARY
 
Honestly, Battles of Legend Terminal Revenge didn't really change much for Red Dragon Archfiend. All Shining Star Dragon and Red Lotus King add to the strategy are strong but niche powerups to the deck. The strategy remains the same - a few negates, mass fieldwipes, and gigantic dragon bodies that are easily accessible and summonable (honestly that's how I like it anyways)! I just wanted an excuse to make another video and guide for this extremely fun combo synchro strategy for one of my favourite Yugioh characters - the "Crimson King" Jack Atlas! 
 
WIELD ABSOLUTE POWERFORCE, BE THE CRIMSON KING AND SYYNNKRRROOOO SHOOOKAAANN!!!

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Kailyn Cooksey-Garcia

Tournament: Omaha WCQ Regional – June 30th 2024

Placement: Top 4

It's based on 2012 Chaos dragons; uses the Lightsworn cards to fuel the grave and provide non-summon mills through recharge / charge. Any milled light is easily recyclable through your extenders and functionally 7 copies of Dimensional Alchemist (through Nova Summoner and Shining Angel). The extenders all regulate grave count as well for krystia and are all beaters that can win games by themselves. The remaining fairy engine of honest and herald are all very strong hand traps that allow you to have a low regular trap count while maintaining defense and trading cards efficiently. Unlike standard fairies you're not as focused on a slower grind game or crashing recruiters to reach Krystia, as a single lightsworn mill had a 50% chance of netting you two fairies. The recruiters main purpose is getting Dimensional Alchemist or Honest. It's the Lightsworn mills or making a synchro with Soul of Purity and Light and herald that get you to Kristya.

The 5 bricks in Soul of Purity and Light and Sky Scourge Enrise are necessary, and they make any milled card a Dimensional Alchemist target. In some cases, side out 1 Scourge, especially when siding things like fader out to avoid Deck Devastation Virus. They also fix the biggest issue with fairies, which is the speed and heavy normal summon reliance. One mill with a Lightsworn will almost always make Soul of Purity and Light and Sky Scourge Enrise live or almost live as well. At 20 fairies you've effectively got a 50% chance to mill 2 with any mill three effect. Soul of Purity and Light and Sky Scourge Enrise are also both herald targets in hand. The fairy count makes herald live almost every time, and if you use a herald any Soul of Purity and Light is also instantly live. Both correct fairy over mill as well, which can happen fairly often. So they can brick, but one lyla / ryko / charge / recharge unbricks them almost every time and they're what makes this version of the deck so fast.

Needle Ceiling in the side is for going against dragon turbo and amaryllis and frogs. Going 2nd it's huge: just set a monster on an established board, and it acts as a quick play Torrential Tribute that doesn't kill your guys. Soul Takers go in against Gladiator Beasts, frogs, machina, stun and anything that summons vanitys against you. Decree is should go in against Gladiator Beasts. Unfortunately, Gladiator Beasts and Machina are still your two hardest matchups. Against Blackwings, take out 1 Enrise and 1 Fader, a Solar Recharge, the Treacherous Trap Hole and a Ryko (if going 2nd), then put in the MST, 2x Decree, 2x Herald of Purple Light and Cydras. Against Vayu, crows go in as well. You can reduce Deck Devastation Virus targets by cutting out an angel.

Metaphys as an archetype focuses around self-banishing and gaining advantage the turn after. With the current level of support available, I don't feel the archetype can ever hold up in modern Yu-Gi-Oh as a meta pick, but it can find a niche in graveyard heavy metas. The deck struggles against back row removal, and often has trouble picking up speed, but once momentum is established you start to outvalue your opponent's plays quickly and overwhelm them. 

Metaphys: The Metaphys engine is pretty searchable and recycles itself, so certain cards can be run at lower numbers without too much of a hit in consistency. Metaphys Ragnarok is a starter that can also get you into Synchro monsters, or use battle damage to summon another Metaphys card from deck. Metaphys Daedalus and Metaphys Nephthys are both board wipes you can set up, and Metaphys Decoy Dragon is probably your strongest recurrable material, and it just so happens to have a combat trick as well, so you can cheat out a board wipe in the battle phase. Asymmetaphys is a powerful spell that filters our Metaphys cards while also having good board effects on the first Metaphys banish each turn. Metaphys Dimension is a hyper powerful archetypal removal and a value engine, with both effects going off easily. Metaphys Factor is your field spell, and it protects your monster activations while also facilitating a later explosive turn.

Banishment: Since you want your side banished anyways, you'll want to run the three banishing floodgates, Dimension Shifter , Dimensional Fissure , and Macro Cosmos , all of which can set you up while debilitating your opponent. Aloof Lupine is another starter that can banish your Metaphys monsters in a pinch, but his main job is to banish Necroface from deck, using a second Necroface or an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring from hand, as this will not only hopefully banish stuff you want to see hit, while taking options away from your opponent. Gold Sarcophagus is the single best starter in the deck, so we're also running three Crossout Designator to work as archetypal Gold Sarcs, since your Metaphys effects trigger outside the negation window. Nemeses Keystone is a fantastic free material that also reloads your deck with the important monsters. Lastly, we have Giant Rex and Shiranui Spiritmaster in the deck to get further benefit from mass banishing, the latter also being a Zombie for Aloof/Necro synergy. 

Interaction: After both your main engine and your banishing engine, your interaction package can look a little light. Ash Blossom is a great hand trap that we can use for other purposes if it's a dead draw. Triple Tactics Talent is a good multitool for the deck, providing three great options to balance the game in our favour. We're also running both Called by the Grave and Infinite Impermanence as crossout targets, the former to protect D Shifter.

Extra Deck: Ragnarok being a tuner allows for easier Synchro summons, while the recurrable and temporary board building lends itself nicely to Link summons. I:P Masquerena is your strongest card in the extra deck, and would be worth running at 2-3 if the space allowed, since it both protects your link monsters summoned with it and allows you to use your recurrable materials on both players' turns. S:P Little Knight is a fantastic card to not only protect your board and debilitate your opponent's, but it also perpetuates some of your banish cards. The main Link boss in the deck is Topologic Zeroboros since it gets massive after even a short engine run, and can wipe the board on the opponent's turn to facilitate a one-shot when it comes back on your turn. On the Synchro side, we've got Dark Dimension Soldier to help us recur Necroface or Kaleido Chick, and Centur-Ion Auxila to protect our back row. Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying is the top boss monster on the Synchro side, being both a beater and a debilitator. Angel of Zera is a self-recurring beater that can clear towers after a couple Necroface hits, then be used as material for the next play. We're also running Psychic End Punisher since our deck will need to come from behind often, and it can rev our engine while clearing the opponent's board.

Side Deck: Lunalight Kaleido Chick is an interesting tech card that can deny battle phase activations, and would be sided in against Tenpai; while not easy to banish on the opponent's turn, it could be used as material with I:P or sent with S:P. Summoning Curse is a way to punish decks focused on special summoning while also giving you potential gas. The two extra Macros should be sided in against decks with recurrable spell/traps, sometimes over two Fissures. Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju is the best kaiju for the deck, since after an Asymmetaphys it only needs a single-proc Ragnarok to beat over. Ghost Mourner & Moonlit Chill can be sided in when Ash isn't the best fit, or as a crossout target. The rest of the Side Deck is filled with cards you'll want to crossout in order to maintain your board and your plan. 

Options: Metaphys Factor, Asymmetaphys, and Metaphys Dimension are highly mutable when it comes to numbers, and will likely have the most variation between decks. Having multiple copies of I:P in the extra deck lets you repeat the process on multiple turns without being forced to use Keystone to reset it. Summon Gate is another floodgate that can be used over Summoning Curse, since most of your extra deck plays are minimal each turn. Underworld Goddess of the Closed World is also a fantastic I:P target, being able to tribute their monsters on their turn. Accesscode Talker can make for good interaction in the extra deck as well, but it's second effect won't be as usable under Macro.

Building Notes: The deck can definitely gain consistency by trimming, but a somewhat larger deck also gives us more of an ability to self banish. I've found that 42-46 cards feels good depending on the build. I've also neglected some of the other common hand traps and interaction cards due to mechanical interactions, cards such as Droll & Lock Bird , Forbidden Droplet , and Effect Veiler are shut off under Macro so I'm less inclined to include them as either interaction or a crossout target. However, your Crossout package is where you have the most choice dependant on local and current meta, but also the least space; I've included a more basic package focused more on protecting our back row. And please, D.D. Crow me, I dare you.

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Jared Darcy

deck_description: don't bother with the side deck it's useless
Slightly chaotic build of Evil Eye with a little more room for unlikely comebacks and painful survival. Not optimal by any means, but it'll viably reach diamond or so.
18 staples and good consistency and Dragite can resolve the first effect with Nibiru

Introduction

This Danger Dark World deck is designed to be more well-rounded - defensive and resilient. Duels last longer and you're less screwed if the Sillva hand-rip strategy does not work (the deck is inconsistent by nature + opponent's handtraps).

Most Danger Dark World decks primarily focus on drawing and maximizing offensive capabilities, they are not as resilient going second nor lasting more than the first few turns. This decklist includes hand traps and negates to prevent a bigger board on your opponent's side of the field. 

Note: the names of specific cards are italicized.

Design Choices

  • Handtraps - prevents opponent from setting up more negates and a bigger board 
  • Goldd, Wu-Lord of Dark World (78004197) - Sillva is useless if you're going second, and you're not guaranteed to go first in the first duel of a match. 
  • Two Dark World Archives (76672730) 
    • "Get the ball rolling" 
    • Doctrine: use the 2nd effect before using the 1st effect of Dark World Archives
      • 2nd effect
        • Results in card advantage
        • Draws twice more cards than The Gates of Dark World 
        • Can be activated on your opponent's turn. 
          • Dark World Puppetry, Dark World Punishment, Dark World Accession, Dark Deal, Grapha Dragon Overlord of Dark World, Clorless Choas King of Dark World 
          • Allows you to draw and discard on your opponent's turn - serves as the best possible interrupt for this deck.
        • To activate it on your turn, use the following cards: The Gates of Dark World, Dark World Accession, Genta Gateman of Dark World
        • More useful than the 1st effect of Dark World Archives
      • 1st effect
        • negates the benefit of hand-advantage
        • only used if you can't discard
          • you're in a bad place if you can't do this (the deck is designed to do this) 
        • 1st effect is only useful after you have finished setting the board 
          • During your turn, you're going to bounce all your monsters. 
          • Use the first effect after you finish bouncing your monsters. 
    • Most decklists include one, they should include two. 
  • Black Rose Moonlight Dragon (33698022)  
    • With the handtraps and lack of normal summons, synchro summoning a lvl 7 monster is more common than you think. 
    • This synchro monster is a good form of self-defence in Yugioh 
  • Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder (90448279) 
    • Very good form of self-defence in Yugioh
  • Tornado Dragon (6983839)
    • On a case-by-case basis, Number 60: Dugares the Timeless, might not be useful. 
    • Tornado Dragon can pop a spell/trap on your turn and your opponent's turn - serves as an interrupt.
    • Can pop more than Knightmare Pheonix
  • Dark World Puppetry (30284022)
    • To get rid of your opponent's bullsh*it GY effects
    • Allows you to summon Genta Gateman of Dark World on your opponent's turn
    • Allows you to active Dark World Archives on your opponent's turn

 

Side Deck Design Choices

  • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring (14558127) - only to counter Branded Fusion or Imsety Glory of Horus
  • Board breakers (Raigeki + Feather Duster) - sometimes it is easier to break an opponent's board than to waste 10 cards worth of resources. 
  • Dark World Punishment (3167439)- only to counter Floowandareze 
  • Dark Deal (65824822)
    • High-risk, high reward card
    • Able to discard on opponent's turn for the best effect
    • Able to activate Dark World Archives on your opponent's turn
    • Negates spell without explicitly negating a spell

 

Below is for duelists who are unfamiliar and are thinking of adopting a Danger Dark World deck:

For Beginners: General Characteristics of a Typical Danger Dark World Deck

  • Primarily focus on drawing cards and drawing only, with the aim of handing-looping Sillva. 
    • Effective strategy when it works
    • Convoluted and requires a lot of steps.
      • More moving parts = more points of failure
      • Can require "the perfect hand"
  • Advantages
    • Has great offensive capabilities
      • ability to summon a lot of monsters without a normal summon 
      • ability to many pop cards with Grapha, Reign-Beaux, and Bigfoot
    • Fewer areas of vulnerability because of the lack of on-field effects 
  • Cons
    • Gives opponents too much opportunity to build an impeccable board, making it unbearable going second. 
      • Lack of hand traps
      • Lack of negates
      • Lack of effects during your opponent's turn
    • Extremely susceptible to handtraps (Droll & Lock Bird, and Ash Blossom) and any form of negates

Author's note 

If you have read this far, thank you! I had used the Danger Dark World deck for a year before moving to Labyrnth. I experimented with Dark Worlds over and over again. I tried various cards and strategies. I see that most Dark World decks are draw-and-draw only. I wanted to show that Dark Worlds can do more than that. I made this decklist to broaden the Dark World strategy and so that you don't have to go through mud and blood to find these strategies. Once again, thank you for reading!

deck_excerpt: Freeze the game to a halt with this oppressive control strategy
deck_description:
This control deck aims to either rush into Lancea for Raiho/warlock interruptions or set up a Kosmoclor/curse lock on your opponent. If you get to go first, then swap in barrier statues and dimensional barriers for additional pressure on the opponent. Defender is useful against Tenpai and other go second strategies, other cards in the side are for use cases with Crossout or when you're forced to go second. 

 

If you're looking for more ways to make synchro 10's, deep sea diva with guitar is a one card combo that I opted not to use in favor of normalling Aegerine.  Guitar can also banish itself to trigger Chengying which can be useful for the grind game.

 

If you have little knight, go ahead and use her. Personally, I can't afford to blow that much money on a single card (she literally would double the deck's cost).

deck_excerpt: For when you want the rage of the ocean to down your opponents.
deck_description:
Hello, welcome!

I know I said that I'd do a spright deck, however that's taking alot longer than expected because of... stuff (mainly me experimenting with combos).  Instead, I'm going to do this umi deck. This isn't really a combo-style deck so this is -probably- going to be shorter, and different, than others.

"Umi" is a card that was was released on the 8th of march 2002 it's a field spell that has the following effect: Aqua monsters on the field gain 200 ATK/DEF, also all Machine and Pyro monsters on the field lose 200 ATK/DEF... it's very bad, but during the years of 2002 - 2010 umi got a moderate amount of support from the meh Torpedo Fish to the psudo zeus that is Levia-Dragon - Daedalus, however in 2021 - 2022 we got support that made "umi" a cohesive stratagy... and it's a control deck. Since this is a control deck this guide is going to be formated differently, I'll explain all the cards and some synergies that make them work so well together. This deck can definately top a locals and maybe a regonals because no one is really prepared to see this, however one downside is that it isn't very good againt removal that can: tribute, destroy (though some cards have foating effects), banish ALL of those can clear the board so be careful. If your opponent figures out which cards to take out first (Electric Jellyfish) they can ruin this deck.

First of all is Adularia of the June Moon with Marincess Coral Anemone.

These work together well because they both manage to get Barrier Statue of the Torrent out on the field if you control a face up card in your spel/trap zones you can (if Adularia of the June Moon is in your hand):
link 2 WATER monsters into Marincess Coral Anemone (this can be achieved by Kairyu-Shin's Dark Reef) > activate Adularia of the June Moon in hand to special summon itself > use Adularia of the June Moon's effect to send Barrier Statue of the Torrent to the GY > activate Marincess Coral Anemone to special summon a WATER monster with less than 1500 ATK (Barrier Statue of the Torrent) to the field.
Barrier Statue of the Torrent floodgates the opponent so that they can only special summon WATER monsers, it's useful when your opponent has "outed"(removed) your main floodgate Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin. 

Some of our direct umi support comes from Doom Kraken:
A level 4 WATER Aqua monster with the folloing effect:
If "umi" is on the field (Quick Effect): You can target 1 WATER monster you control, except "Doom Kraken", and 1 monster your opponent controls; Special Summon this card from your hand, and if you do, return that monster you control to the hand, and if you do that, destroy that opponent's monster. When an opponent's monster declares an attack: You can return this card to the hand, and if you do, negate that attack. You can only use each effect of  "Doom Kraken" once per turn.

It's a versatile card that can spring on the board with a bit of removal tacked on it, Doom Kraken can also stop attacks which is a pretty good effect. The targeted return has the ability to not olny doge attacks but to also remove unwated monsters on the field. Doom Kraken allows you to maintain field presence and protect key cards from destrucion.

Electric Jellyfish is a card that we use in the deck:
A level 4 WATER Aqua monster with the following effect:
You can send 1 "umi" from your hand, Deck, or face-up field to the GY; Special Summon 1 WATER monster from your hand. When your opponent activates a monster effect, or Spell Card or effect, while "umi" is on the field (Quick Effect): You can negate that effect, then, you can make this card gain 600 ATK/DEF. You can only use each effect of "Electric Jellyfish" once per turn.

Electric Jellyfish can help extend our plays by sending an "umi" from our field/deck to the GY we can summon a plethora of WATER monsters including  -but not limited to- Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin, Mega Fortress Whale, Citadel Whale and even General Raiho of the Ice Barrier (a cool floodgate card that negates a card unless the discard cards). It also has an effect negation effect that can disrupt our opponent or respond to our opponents attempts to stop our plays, this also causes our Electric Jellyfish to gain 600 ATK/DEF which can also make a big wall that our opponent can't beat over. It's effects can be used for a small 2 card combo with Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin but we'll cover that later. Ovarall Electric Jellyfish can swarm the field with floodgates and create some defensive plays whilst controling the field.

Warrior of Atlantis:
A level 4 WATER Aqua monster withthe following effect:
You can discard this card to the Graveyard; add 1 "A Legendary Ocean" from your Deck to your hand.

I mean it's pretty self explainable - it searches the field spell. It can however be a material used for an xyz monster if you wish so.

On to the penultimate card - Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin: 
A level 5 WATER Sea Serpent monster with the following effect:
While "umi" is on the field, each player can only control 1 face-up non-WATER monster. (If a player controls 2 or more, they must send some to the GY so they only control 1.) During your Main Phase: You can add from your Deck to your hand 1 "umi", 1 "Kairyu-Shin" Spell/Trap, or 1 "Sea Stealth" Spell/Trap. You can only use this effect of "Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin" once per turn.

This poweful floodgate restricts your opponent from cintroling more that 1 non-water monster (which being in a FIRE dominated format is great) it's also a self synergy because it dosn't affect the deck in any way. The search effect can also help build a tougher board by adding either Kairyu-Shin's Dark Reef or Sea Stealth Attack to control and swarm the boards, Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin is the main boss monster for the deck and is the main way to stop your opponent.

A small combo to remember is Electric Jellyfish + Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin + Kairyu-Shin's Dark Reef or Sea Stealth Attack with an "umi" on field

normal summon Electric Jellyfish > Electric Jellyfish effect send "umi" from deck to GY; special summon Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin > add either Kairyu-Shin's Dark Reef or Sea Stealth Attack (whichever you don't have) > set both > end phase
opponent's turn: Sea Stealth Attack > ativate both Kairyu-Shin's Dark Reef sending "umi" to the GY;

RESOLVE:

1. summon 2 WATER monsters from your deck that mention "umi" (e.g. Mega Fortress Whale and Doom Kraken)

2. re-acrivate "umi" from the GY

GLHF opponent.

The last monster today is Mega Fortress Whale:
A level 7 WATER Fish monster with the folloing effect:
If "umi" is on the field: You can activate this effect; your WATER monsters can attack directly this turn. During your opponent's Battle Phase (Quick Effect): You can target 1 face-up monster your opponent controls; destroy it. If this card on the field is destroyed by battle or card effect: You can either add to your hand or Special Summon 1 WATER Warrior monster from your Deck or GY. You can only activate the effects of Mega Fortress Whale once per turn.

This is a great card. This can not only close out games, but is also free removal during the battle phase. IF (because it is an absolute whale of a monster) it's destroyed it's destruction effect can special summon 1 WATER Warrior monster from the deck, and here we play General Raiho of the Ice Barrier yet another floodgate, it prevents your opponent from activating card effects unless they discard a card (I don't need to tell you why that's good though).

The spells and traps allow us to further control what happens on the board whilst searching monsters for further consistancy, this makes the deck a joy to play as alot of these cards search and you have access to basically the entire deck, the main ones are:

- Fish Sonar 

- Foolish Burial Goods & Ice Barrier

- Kairyu-Shin's Dark Reef 

These all search monsters in one way or another - Ice Barrier is also some interuption if you draw into it - 

The important spells/traps (that don't search) are:

- umi obviously

- Sea Stealth II 

- Sea Stealth Attack 

These cards allow you to doge effects keeping monsters on the field whilst steadly increacing the pressure on our opponent using Sea Stealth II summoning a monster evry turn.

The extra deck can be anything as we don't really need it I've chosen hese cards as 

Anyway that is all for this deck, overall is a very, very good deck that can setup multiple floodgates and negations as well as some destrucion/removal so we don't really need to play hand traps like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Nibiru, the Primal Being but if you want to, you can. This deck is fun, fast paced for a control deck and can close out games quite quickly.

Thats all you need to know REMEMBER this isn't the best or only way to play umi so change the deck as you wish and as allways stay safe and have fun (: !

signed @dracob

deck_excerpt: This is just my potential list for when the new cards from "The Infinite Forbidden" come out, as I am very excited for them.
deck_description:
The main thing this deck is to do, in order to get out the 'The Unstoppable Exodia Incarnate' is pitch the cards to the graveyard (so youre not having to keep them in hand and especially not wasting your normal summon for turn on them either.) and use "Magicalized Fusion" to get the big boss out, or if youre feeling up to it, and normal summoning a piece just for fun and using it to get 'The Legendary Exodia Incarnate' would be fun too, but only IF NEEDED as another body to hit with, should you do that. I'd even use Legendary Exodia Incarnate as Timaeus fodder to be honest. 

 

Shining Sarc and Dark Magician go hand-in-hand, as both effects can be used simultaneously, use Shining Sarc to get Dark Magicain. Then, use Dark Magician's effect to special summon from hand, if you do happen to have 'Dark Magical Circle' on field, 'Dark Magician The Magician of Black Magic' DOES activate the effect of being able to banish a card as per it's effect saying, 'This card's name becomes "Dark Magician" while on the field.' So you can even possibly utilize Dark Magic Attack in too. Blue Dragon Summoner and Summoner's Wand are in here to help possibly even get Exodia Pieces for a potential win, if you can pull it off. 

 

Contract of Exodia, Exodia Necross, and The Legendary Exodia Incarnate are mainly just possibilities, as you'll mainly put the Exodia pieces into the graveyard (as mentioned above) to utilize Magicalized Fuison. The "Raging Hellfire - Exodd Flame" is also a possibility to utilize The Legendary Exodia Incarnate and Exodia Necross, as youre able to shuffle all 5 pieces form the Banishment BACK into the deck. 

 

Another fun little gimmick that is present in this deck is a fun 'loop'. This loop is using 'Obliterate!' to send Dark Magician the Magician of Black Magic back to hand to pitch an Exodia piece then summoning DMtMoBM back from your hand if Shining Sarc is on the field. 

 

A possible tech I may add is 'Dark Magician the Dragon Knight', as it will protect your spells/traps, so then youre able to keep your back row safer.

 

Any suggestions and/or discussions will be fun to have on this theory deck! 

Thanks for reading! (I know, we don't like reading)

deck_name: Beginner's Guide to Snake-Eye Fire King (July 2024)
deck_excerpt: Fire King continues it's royal reign of Masterduel ladder with it's bestie - Snake-Eye!
deck_description:
Despite the banlist hits, Snake-Eye continues its Tier 1 dominance with it's many incarnations - this time with Fire King! 

Fire King has finally arrived in Masterduel with the selection pack Lord of Dimensions, and when these royal beasts are mixed with Snake-Eye, they are a nearly unstoppable force! Fire King provides so much extension, recursion, bodies and utility to the Snake-Eyes strategy. Almost EVERYTHING floats you into either more giant beatsticks on field or more resources in-hand. Piloted properly, Snake-Eye Fire King definitely is the #1 deck on ladder, being able to deal with Maxx "C," counter stun decks, and dominate regular meta decks! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING
 
This strategy is composed of two archetypes, FIRE KING and SNAKE-EYE. Since this strategy has two full archetypes in it, there are less STAPLES that are in the deck but that is exchanged for more "gas" to propel the gameplan forward. 
 
The SNAKE-EYE cards take a step aside and are merely a supportive crutch for the strategy. Snake-Eyes Ash starts up the entire gameplan, so despite the banlist hits, 10 cards search it (3 Diabellstarr, 1 WANTED, 2 Poplar, 1 Original Sinful-Spoils, 3 Bonfire) in addition to having 1 of Ash granting a total of 11 starters! With that many starters, this Snake-Eyes portion of the deck is surprisingly consistent.
 
The FIRE KING cards take the royal centre stage in this strategy. Compared to it's "pure" variant, the Fire King package in this deck is compact, comprised of 1 Fire King Island, 1 Sanctuary, 1 Ponix, 1 Sacred Garunix, 1 Avatar Garunix, 1 Arvata, 1 Sky Burn and 1 Circle of Fire Kings. 3 Fire King Consort is used since it's a great starter/combo piece and 3 High Avatar Kirin since it allows monsters to dodge targeting effects like Imperm and Effect Veiler. 
 
The STAPLES featured in this deck are the usual suspects in Masterduel - the 12 card "Maxx C" package (3 Ash, 3 Maxx, 2 Called By, 1 Crossout and 2 Gamma + 1 Driver) so that you can come out on top of the "Maxx C Minigame." 1 Nibiru, Droll, and Imperm are popular staples and Crossout targets to negate. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Snake-Eye Fire King is a powerful combo deck that can link spam like no tomorrow. After the initial Snake-Eye combo, there are a ton of extenders such as Flamberge Dragon's "soul charge" of level 1 fires and Promethean Princess' summon of any fire monster from GY. Similarly to the "Cyberse pile" decks, Snake-Eye Fire King's immense swarming potential allow that enable the deck to link climb to incredible heights. Not only that, the deck is resilient enough to play through high impact handtraps like Nibiru, Droll, even Dimension Shifter! 
 
The Fire King variant of Snake-Eye differs from the other Snake-Eye decks since it isn't a linear deck - depending on what Fire King cards you have, you can extend extremely far and break boards, even before normal summoning Snake-Eyes Ash. Sometimes, you can even get 4 bodies on field to create Apollousa before the 5th summon so you can insulate your Snake-Eyes combo. The great variety in boards that certain hands make and in certain gamestate depend on the skill and decision making of the duelist. So practice with this deck is key, since it is fairly more complicated than your regular Snake-Eyes deck!
 
A singular uninterrupted Snake-Eyes Ash gets you through everything and provides you with a whopping many interruptions and incredible amounts of resources as follow-up for next turn. 
 
Snake-Eyes Ash =  1 targeted destruction of a monster (Promethean Princess) + 2-4 monster negates (Apollousa) or S:P Little Knight Banish + Linkuriboh (battle protection) + Heatsoul (draw 1) + Zealantis (destruction during Battle Phase) + Sacred Garunix (gigantic body that summons from GY and destroy 1 with Kirin) + Raging Phoenix (gigantic body that summons from GY) . 
  1. Normal summon Snake-Eyes Ash. Activate Snake Ash's effect to search for Snake Poplar from deck. 
  2. Activate Poplar's effect to summon itself from hand when searched. 
  3. Activate Poplar's effect when summoned to search for Original Sinful Spoils. 
  4. Link summon Linkuriboh using Poplar. Activate Poplar's effect when it leaves the field to place itself in the backrow. 
  5. Activate Original Sinful Spoils sending Poplar in the backrow to the GY to summon from deck Ponix. 
  6. Activate Ponix's effect to search for Fire King Sanctuary. 
  7. Activate Fire King Sanctuary to place Fire King Island on the field from deck. 
  8. Activate Snake-Eye Ash's effect to send itself and Sanctuary to the GY to summon from deck Snake-Eye Oak. 
  9. Activate Oak's on-summon effect to summon from GY Snake-Eye Ash. 
  10. Activate Oak's effect send itself and Ash to summon from deck Flamberge Dragon. 
  11. Activate Fire King Island's effect to destroy Ponix and search for Sacred Garunix. 
  12. Activate Sacred Garunix's effect to summon itself from hand. Activate Garunix's on-summon effect to destroy High Avatar Kirin from hand. 
  13. Activate Kirin's GY effect to summon from the GY Ponix. 
  14. Link summon I:P Masquerena using Flamberge Dragon + Sacred Garunix. 
  15. Activate Flamberge Dragon's effect to summon from GY Snake-Eye Ash and Oak. 
  16. Link summon Promethean Princess using I:P Masquerena + Linkuriboh. 
  17. Activate Promethean Princess' effect to summon from GY Flamberge Dragon. 
  18. Activate Flamberge Dragon's effect to place I:P Masquerena in the backrow. 
  19. Link summon Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf using Promethean Princess + Snake-Eyes Ash. 
  20. Tribute Snake-Eyes Oak with Linkuriboh to summon it from the GY, summon it underneath Sunlight Wolf so its link arrow is pointing to it. 
  21. Activate Sunlight Wolf's effect to take High Avatar Kirin from your GY to hand. (You can add any fire monster like Ash Blossom this way). 
  22. Link summon Heatsoul using Sunlight Wolf + Linkuriboh. 
  23. Activate Heatsoul's effect to pay 1000 lifepoints and draw 1 card. 
  24. Link summon Salamangreat Raging Phoenix using Ponix + Heatsoul. 
  25. Link summon Zealantis using Raging Phoenix as the whole material. 
  26. Activate Zealantis' effect to banish itself and all other monsters on your field and return them to the field. Place Zealantis in a Main Monster Zone where it can be easily co-linked Promethean Princess.
  27. During your opponent's turn, summon I:P Masquerena from the backrow. 
  28. Activate I:P Masquerena to link summon. Either link summon S:P Little Knight or Apollousa as needed.
  29. During your opponent's turn, when your fire monster gets destroyed, float into the field from the GY with Raging Phoenix and Sacred Garunix. Remember, Garunix can destroy Kirin from deck, and Kirin destroys a card as it reborns something!
GOING FIRST, a singular Snake-Eyes Ash grants you a TON of resources, materials and interruptions. You get several monster negates, and banishes, and you get an insane resource loop that constantly feeds your hand and field with immense amounts of resources. With that, you should be able to get ahead of your opponent and win in a grindgame or quickly OTK with overwhelming power. 
 
GOING SECOND, the Snake-Eyes strategy features a ton of handtraps to weaken your opponent's gamestate and alot of gas to enable the duelist to power through interruption. As you combo up, you can methodically remove your opponent's field using Flamberge Dragon's non-destruction removal, Kirin's destruction and Accesscode can be made for about 3 pops due to the different attribute link materials in the GY. Finally, you can OTK in a heart beat with Zealantis, Promethean Princess and Raging Phoenix OTK. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Both Snake-Eyes and Fire King does a lot of actions that involves having no monsters on the field - meaning that Psy-Frame Gamma is almost always live! Alot of players on ladder leave their Ash Blossom for the Original Sinful Spoils summoning a card from deck, and since the card leaves your field empty, you can Gamma their Ash Blossom! When that interaction happens, people usually leave. 
  • If you lose out on the Maxx "C" minigame, try to end your board on Flamberge Dragon. For the price of allowing your opponent to draw 1 more card, you can end on a 3000 ATK body and follow-up for next turn since the card floats into your searchers in the GY. 
  • Hiita and Dharc can summon a monster from your opponent's GY (for example, summon your opponent's Ash Blossom or D.D. Crow) and you can either make Selene (typically for Accesscode) or more importantly, Promethean Princess. if your GY is already set-up, this play allows you to get back to your gameplan by summoning a crucial Fire monster from the GY, like Snake-Eyes Ash, Poplar or Flamberge Dragon. 
  • If you have Snake-Eyes Ash and you drew into Original Sinful Spoils already, when you search with Poplar take Snake-Eyes Divine Temple instead so that it's an additional extender. The extra card in the backrow serves as an extender for your Snake-Eyes cost to send a card on the field to the GY.  
  • Snake-Eyes Fire King summons so many times (even on the opponent's turn!) that you'd sometimes find yourself in the awkward position of having no more space on your board! Be careful of this scenario. A good way to get around this situation during your opponent's turn is to link away as much monsters as possible for I:P Masquerena. 
  • Since all your interruption is centered around your monsters, be careful about your Apollousa being stolen by your opponent (happens surprisingly a lot). A "talents" or change of heart on your Apollousa is often devastating and is enough to break your board since you'll be facing down your own mass negates. 
  • You'll encounter a lot of Snake-Eye mirror matches on ladder. When facing a rival Snake-Eyes player, negate your opponent's Flamberge Dragon, especially by using Crossout or Called By the Grave. This prevents their target removal of your cards and severely limits their link spam. Also, try to prevent your opponent from summoning or using Hiita, since she can also use your entire GY with all it's effect monsters!
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
     
CONCLUDING COMMENTARY
 
It seems like Fire King's royal reign will continue for a while on Masterduel ladder, since Snake-Eyes still exists as a viable deck. Since Snake-Eye's consistency is being shafted by banlist after banlist, additional strategies need to be added on top so that the deck remains usable. I guess that's one way to coerce hardcore Masterduelists to buy new archetypes like the Fire Kings! 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Combining old school Spirit monsters with Shinobarons
deck_description:
I was mostly inspired to put this deck together by the Shinobaron cards from AGOV and Shinobarons support regular Spirit monsters as well I thought hy not mix some lore so I added a few more generally strong Spirit monsters.

For more detailed info on startegies involving the old school Spirit monsters you can refer to Zeraslight's decklist since they did a bang up job going through all the individual explanations with their article in Pure Spirit Mind - YGOPRODeck and I did take some inspiration from it.

Of course this deck is in no way something to bring to a competitive event unless you REALLY want to either lose every game or get lucky they can't out your Amano-Iwato

Otherwise the deck plays a control strategy (You can also make a case of adding Yata-Garasu as well but unless you can reliably clear the field and still summon him he's not doing a lot) that tries to either lock the opponent out of effects or force them to give up tons of resources. Shinobaroness Peacock for example is a great way to deploy the Amano-lock as long as your opponent has any spells or traps on their field since she pulls Amano-Iwato out of the deck.

The current Side Deck is mostly comprised of toolbox and some additional copies of your one-ofs (in case your opponent has means of removing them from your card pool) or Izanagi who you have to hard draw into for his actually really powerful effect of keeping your Spirits around as much as you want

If there's any more questions and/or things you'd improve you can leave a comment and I'll gladly try addressing them in the future

deck_excerpt: Use the really powerful Fiendsmith engine to power-up Live Twin Spright like never before!
deck_description: I know people have been doing some stuff with Live Twin Fiendsmith, and I really liked that, but I also love Live Twin Spright, so I did my best to mash them together. It's fun, and can put up good end boards, the only downside is the really tight extra and main deck. I'm sure there are better cards/ratios for the extra deck, also if you want to take the main deck down to 40 you can cut the 2nd spright red and the gamma burst. I do feel that the 2nd spright red comes up, but you can cut it and be largely fine.

Un-serious OTK deck using Gate Guardians. In a few test runs, seems like I'm able to hit an FTK fairly consistently (~70% of the time) without disruption. Need to test it and also test out swapping out some of the cards.

Goal is to bring out 3 different Gate Guardian monsters in a single turn for a beatdown OTK.

- Armageddon Knight -> Dark Guardian into Graveyard -> Summon Gate Guardian Combined -> Burial from a different dimension for second gate guardian -> shuffle pieces back into deck to summon Dark Guardian is dream combo

- Extra-foolish Burial (drop a gate guardian monster from extra deck into graveyard) followed by Dark Element seems a bit tricky to pull off and inconsistent.

- Card Destruction may not be that worthwhile here. Dark world dealings appears to work the best since you get to draw first then decide what to discard. Hand destruction is okay. Dragged down to the grave is probably the worst to use here.
